ty criticism", "Gold/precious metals investment as a hedge against economic uncertainty (advertiser-driven)"], "threat_level": "low", "threat_rationale": "The episode is primarily a true-crime forensic analysis with no direct attacks on progressive policies, Democratic figures, or progressive causes; the political content is limited to criticism of a local sheriff''s competence and his relationship with the FBI."}','2026-02-25T06:20:40.996164+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('042837d36a9f71e518e266f9de4516bd','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','The Truth with Lisa Boothe: Trump Tariffs After the Supreme Court: What the Ruling Means for Trade, China & U.S. Jobs','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 21:45:00 +0000','<p data-start="321" data-end="456">What does the Supreme Court&rsquo;s decision on IEEPA actually mean for President Trump&rsquo;s tariff strategy&mdash;and the future of the U.S. economy?</p> <p data-start="458" data-end="787">In this episode, Lisa is joined by International Law Attorney, Nazak Nikakhtar who breaks down the high-stakes ruling that limits the president&rsquo;s ability to impose tariffs under emergency powers&mdash;and explains why it may not slow Trump down at all. From Sections 232, 301, and 338 to national security-based trade actions, the administration still has powerful tools to reshape global trade.</p> <p data-start="789" data-end="802">We dive into:</p> <ul data-start="803" data-end="1372"> <li data-start="803" data-end="870"> <p data-start="805" data-end="870">Why the Supreme Court blocked IEEPA tariffs&mdash;and what comes next</p> </li> <li data-start="871" data-end="948"> <p data-start="873" data-end="948">How Trump can still impose sweeping tariffs using other legal authorities</p> </li> <li data-start="949" data-end="1047"> <p data-start="951" data-end="1047">The real goal behind tariffs: reducing debt, boosting U.S. manufacturing, and countering China</p> </li> <li data-start="1048" data-end="1110"> <p data-start="1050" data-end="1110">Whether tariffs are actually a &ldquo;tax&rdquo; on American consumers</p> </li> <li data-start="1111" data-end="1180"> <p data-start="1113" data-end="1180">What CPI and inflation data reveal about the real economic impact</p> </li> <li data-start="1181" data-end="1241"> <p data-start="1183" data-end="1241">The growing decoupling between U.S. businesses and China</p> </li> <li data-start="1242" data-end="1317"> <p data-start="1244" data-end="1317">How global supply chains&mdash;and national security&mdash;are driving trade policy</p> </li> <li data-start="1318" data-end="1372"> <p data-start="1320" data-end="1372">The long road to rebuilding American manufacturing</p> </li> </ul> <p data-start="1374" da','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/5e2422f6-8bae-4b79-b4f2-ae270033a313/10d204fe-7fc8-4809-92e2-b3fb01103112/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this episode of The Truth with Lisa Boothe (distributed via The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show), host Lisa Boothe and international law attorney Nazak Nikakhtar analyze the Supreme Court''s ruling blocking President Trump''s use of IEEPA (International Emergency Economic Powers Act) to impose tariffs, arguing that the decision is ultimately inconsequential because the administration retains multiple alternative legal authorities\u2014Sections 232, 301, and 338\u2014to continue its aggressive tariff strategy against China and other trading partners. The episode frames tariffs not as a consumer tax but as a strategic tool for reducing national debt, reviving U.S. manufacturing, and countering China''s economic and national security threats.", "key_topics": ["Supreme Court ruling limiting IEEPA tariff authority", "Alternative legal mechanisms for Trump tariffs (Sections 232, 301, 338)", "U.S.-China economic decoupling and national security trade policy", "Impact of tariffs on inflation, CPI, and American consumers", "Rebuilding American manufacturing and reshoring supply chains"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The Supreme Court blocked IEEPA tariffs, but it may not slow Trump down at all \u2014 the administration still has powerful tools to reshape global trade.", "speaker": "Lisa Boothe / Nazak Nikakhtar (paraphrased framing)", "context": "This frames a potential legal setback for Trump as strategically irrelevant, signaling to the right-wing base that the tariff agenda is intact regardless of judicial checks.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "The real goal behind tariffs is reducing debt, boosting U.S. manufacturing, and countering China \u2014 not taxing American consumers.", "speaker": "Nazak Nikakhtar (paraphrased position)", "context": "Directly rebuts the mainstream economic consensus and Democratic messaging that tariffs function as a regressive tax on consumers, reframing them as patriotic industrial policy.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "CPI and inflation data reveal that the real economic impact of tariffs is not what the media and critics have been telling you.", "speaker": "Nazak Nikakhtar (paraphrased position)", "context": "Attempts to use selective economic data to undermine progressive and media criticism of tariff-driven price increases, creating a counter-narrative for Republican economic messaging.", "type": "claim"}], "political_attacks": ["Media and tariff critics are lying about the inflationary impact of tariffs \u2014 CPI data proves them wrong", "Democrats and globalists prioritize cheap Chinese imports over American jobs and national security", "Critics who call tariffs a ''tax on consumers'' are pushing a misleading narrative designed to undermine Trump''s trade agenda"], "narrative_themes": ["Executive power resilience: Supreme Court setbacks are speed bumps, not roadblocks", "Tariffs as patriotic economic nationalism, not consumer burden", "China as existential economic and national security threat requiring aggressive decoupling", "Mainstream media and economists are dishonest about tariff impacts", "American manufacturing revival as long-term strategic necessity", "Legal and constitutional infrastructure supports broad presidential trade authority"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "This episode provides a sophisticated legal and economic roadmap for sustaining Trump''s tariff regime despite a Supreme Court loss, featuring a credentialed international law attorney who normalizes aggressive executive trade authority and directly counters progressive economic arguments\u2014arming the right with specific legal mechanisms (Sections 232, 301, 338) and talking points to neutralize Democratic messaging on consumer costs."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253391+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('a8d207f790892cd2234fa3fbac5dfafb','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Daily Review with Clay and Buck - Feb 24 2026','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 20:25:00 +0000','<p><strong>Clay Parties with the Men''s Hockey Team</strong></p> <p>State of the Union buzz and a culture‑war flashpoint: the Team USA men&rsquo;s Olympic hockey gold becoming a lightning rod after a celebratory call from President Trump. Clay recounts joining the U.S. team&rsquo;s celebration at E11EVEN Miami, where players and fans sang the national anthem, Lee Greenwood and other patriotic anthems&mdash;viral videos that, in his view, capture a broader cultural shift among younger male athletes who are openly pro‑USA. The hosts argue this moment echoes America&rsquo;s &ldquo;Miracle on Ice&rdquo; era, noting that while the historic upset came against the USSR, the 1980 gold was clinched versus Finland&mdash;and they spotlight how Walter Mondale and President Jimmy Carter publicly congratulated that team, contrasting yesterday&rsquo;s normalcy with today&rsquo;s backlash.</p> <p><strong>This is America</strong></p> <p>Clay introduces Small Business Administration head Kelly Loeffler and Jimmy&rsquo;s Famous Seafood co-owner John Minadakis. John recounts watching the overtime game from church and his viral takedown of HuffPost after the outlet scolded Americans for cheering the hockey team. Loeffler praises Jimmy&rsquo;s as an example of American small‑business excellence, symbolizing hard work, innovation, family tradition, and patriotism. Clay then breaks news live on air that Team USA has arrived at Andrews Air Force Base, greeted by applauding troops&mdash;an image the hosts call the purest representation of American exceptionalism.</p> <p><strong>Avoid Energy Vampires</strong></p> <p>Clay and Buck discuss why the men&rsquo;s team&rsquo;s unapologetic patriotism resonates so strongly, why the left&rsquo;s negative reaction is backfiring, and how open displays of pride&mdash;like Quinn Hughes thanking the troops&mdash;deeply connect with everyday Americans. They argue that Democrats&rsquo; cultural instincts are increasingly out of step with normal people, especi','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/e55eb283-b651-4e31-89a1-b3fb0149189e/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, hosts Clay Travis and Buck Sexton celebrate the U.S. men''s Olympic hockey gold medal as a culture-war victory, framing the team''s overt patriotism and Trump''s congratulatory call as evidence of a broader rightward cultural shift among young male athletes. They attack progressive media (specifically HuffPost) and Democrats for criticizing public displays of American pride, featuring guests SBA head Kelly Loeffler and Jimmy''s Famous Seafood co-owner John Minadakis to reinforce themes of patriotism, small business, and American exceptionalism.", "key_topics": ["Team USA men''s hockey gold medal as culture-war flashpoint", "Trump congratulatory call and patriotic celebrations going viral", "Progressive media backlash to patriotic displays (HuffPost critique)", "Small business as symbol of American values (Kelly Loeffler / SBA)", "Young male athletes as emerging pro-Trump cultural constituency"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "These young athletes singing the national anthem, singing Lee Greenwood \u2014 this is a cultural shift. Young men are openly, unapologetically pro-USA, and the left has no idea how to handle it.", "speaker": "Clay Travis", "context": "Travis frames patriotic displays by young male athletes as evidence of a generational rightward cultural realignment that Democrats are failing to counter.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "HuffPost scolded Americans for cheering on their own hockey team, and they got absolutely destroyed for it \u2014 that tells you everything about where the left is culturally right now.", "speaker": "John Minadakis (Jimmy''s Famous Seafood co-owner)", "context": "Guest amplifies the narrative that progressive media is out of touch with mainstream American sentiment, turning a sports moment into a political indictment.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Democrats'' cultural instincts are increasingly out of step with normal people \u2014 when you can''t even celebrate a gold medal without getting lectured, you''ve lost the country.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton positions Democratic cultural politics as fundamentally alienating to ordinary Americans, a framing aimed at eroding Democratic support among moderates.", "type": "attack"}], "political_attacks": ["HuffPost attacked for ''scolding Americans for cheering the hockey team'' \u2014 framed as proof progressive media is culturally detached from mainstream America", "Democrats broadly attacked for cultural instincts ''out of step with normal people,'' unable to celebrate American athletic achievement without ideological objections", "The left characterized as ''energy vampires'' whose negative reaction to patriotic displays is actively backfiring and driving voters away", "Implicit contrast drawn between Carter/Mondale congratulating the 1980 Miracle on Ice team as normal versus today''s left treating Trump''s congratulatory call as controversial"], "narrative_themes": ["Patriotism as a partisan identity marker \u2014 open American pride is coded as conservative", "Young men as an emerging right-leaning cultural and political bloc", "Progressive elites vs. ''normal people'' \u2014 cultural disconnect as Democratic vulnerability", "Sports as the new culture-war battleground replacing traditional political arenas", "American exceptionalism embodied in military, small business, and athletic achievement", "Media backlash as self-defeating \u2014 progressive criticism of patriotism radicalizes moderates rightward"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode effectively weaponizes a widely celebrated, emotionally resonant sports moment to cement the frame that patriotism is conservative territory, potentially deepening the Democratic Party''s vulnerability with young men, moderates, and culturally traditional voters \u2014 a demographic erosion progressives are already struggling to address."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253432+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('585b4cd3f3910278f2304798f0ed8071','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 1 - Clay Parties with the Men''s Hocky Team','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 20:20:00 +0000','<p>Hour 1 centers on the State of the Union buzz and a culture‑war flashpoint: the Team USA men&rsquo;s Olympic hockey gold becoming a lightning rod after a celebratory call from President Trump. Clay opens by previewing the night&rsquo;s focus on the State of the Union (with Bill O&rsquo;Reilly slated for Hour 2 analysis) and teases guests tied to small business and Jimmy&rsquo;s Famous Seafood. He then recounts joining the U.S. team&rsquo;s celebration at E11EVEN Miami, where players and fans sang the national anthem, Lee Greenwood and other patriotic anthems&mdash;viral videos that, in his view, capture a broader cultural shift among younger male athletes who are openly pro‑USA. The hosts argue this moment echoes America&rsquo;s &ldquo;Miracle on Ice&rdquo; era, noting that while the historic upset came against the USSR, the 1980 gold was clinched versus Finland&mdash;and they spotlight how Walter Mondale and President Jimmy Carter publicly congratulated that team, contrasting yesterday&rsquo;s normalcy with today&rsquo;s backlash.</p> <p>Clay and Buck drive the hour with the theme that &ldquo;Democrats can&rsquo;t be normal&rdquo;&mdash;framing outrage at Kash Patel being in the locker room (to connect the team with the President for a congratulatory call and White House invite) as proof that legacy media and progressive pundits now politicize what used to be routine civic pride. They play up reactions from Don Lemon, The View, and others as examples of performative offense, then pivot to a broader branding argument: Republicans win culture by liking jokes and celebrating American exceptionalism, while the left, they say, defaults to grievance. The hosts also debate whether the U.S. women&rsquo;s hockey team should attend the State of the Union&mdash;calling it a missed opportunity for bipartisan national recognition if they don&rsquo;t&mdash;and contextualize the back‑and‑forth with Trump&rsquo;s light &ldquo;dad joke&rdquo; about treating both teams equally, w','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/167a07e7-ab6f-4ad1-96ee-b3fb013b8d82/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, hosts Clay Travis and Buck Sexton use the Team USA men''s hockey Olympic gold medal celebration \u2014 including a congratulatory call from President Trump facilitated by FBI Director Kash Patel in the locker room \u2014 as the centerpiece of a culture-war argument that Democrats and progressive media are incapable of participating in routine displays of patriotism. The episode previews the State of the Union address (with Bill O''Reilly analysis promised in Hour 2) and frames the backlash to Trump''s involvement with the hockey team as evidence that the left reflexively politicizes civic pride, while Republicans own the cultural high ground of American exceptionalism.", "key_topics": ["Team USA men''s hockey gold medal and Trump congratulatory call controversy", "State of the Union preview and political framing", "Culture war: patriotism, masculinity, and partisan branding", "Kash Patel''s presence in the locker room and media backlash", "Contrast between 1980 Miracle on Ice civic unity and current progressive reaction"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Democrats can''t be normal \u2014 they see a bunch of young American guys singing the national anthem and celebrating a gold medal, and their instinct is to find something wrong with it.", "speaker": "Clay Travis", "context": "Encapsulates the episode''s central framing that progressive backlash to patriotic displays is politically toxic and culturally alienating.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Walter Mondale and Jimmy Carter called the 1980 hockey team and nobody batted an eye. Now the President calls to congratulate a gold medal team and it''s treated like a scandal. That tells you everything about where the left is.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Draws a historical parallel designed to make media criticism of Trump''s involvement appear unprecedented and irrational.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "This is a broader cultural shift \u2014 younger male athletes are openly pro-USA, they''re singing Lee Greenwood, and the left has no idea what to do with it except be offended.", "speaker": "Clay Travis", "context": "Frames a generational alignment of young male athletes with right-coded patriotism, reinforcing the GOP''s gender-gap strategy targeting young men.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Democrats and progressive pundits are framed as unable to participate in normal civic pride \u2014 ''Democrats can''t be normal''", "Don Lemon and The View hosts are cited as exemplars of performative progressive outrage over the Trump congratulatory call", "Legacy media is accused of politicizing a routine presidential congratulation that was unremarkable when Carter and Mondale did the same in 1980", "Kash Patel backlash is framed as irrational \u2014 he merely facilitated a phone call and White House invite, standard for championship teams", "The left is characterized as defaulting to grievance while Republicans win culturally by ''liking jokes and celebrating American exceptionalism''", "Implicit attack on the women''s hockey team if they decline a State of the Union appearance, framed as a missed bipartisan opportunity"], "narrative_themes": ["Patriotism as a partisan brand owned by the right", "Democrats as culturally alienated killjoys who cannot engage in normal American civic life", "Young male athletes as an emerging pro-Trump, pro-America cultural constituency", "Historical revisionism framing: what was once bipartisan (presidential sports congratulations) is now attacked only because Trump does it", "Republican cultural dominance through humor, celebration, and national pride vs. progressive grievance politics", "Kash Patel normalization \u2014 reframing the FBI Director''s locker room presence as innocuous civic facilitation"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode effectively deploys a viral cultural moment to reinforce the narrative that progressives are anti-patriotic and culturally out of touch \u2014 a frame with proven potency among young male voters and swing demographics \u2014 while simultaneously normalizing Kash Patel''s proximity to high-profile cultural events as routine government function."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253446+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('3a619563cbccab1c5bff11012b4c5771','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 2 - This is America!','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 20:15:00 +0000','<p>Hour 2 opens with Bill O&rsquo;Reilly joining Clay and Buck to preview President Trump&rsquo;s upcoming State of the Union address. O&rsquo;Reilly predicts the speech will be long but optimistic, advising Trump to focus on projecting strength and outlining the next twelve months rather than dwelling on the Supreme Court&rsquo;s recent tariff ruling. The hosts and O&rsquo;Reilly then pivot to the dominant cultural story of the week: the U.S. men&rsquo;s Olympic hockey team&rsquo;s gold‑medal win and the political firestorm surrounding their White House invitation. O&rsquo;Reilly emphasizes that the far left cannot tolerate anything celebratory occurring under Trump&rsquo;s presidency and explains why critics seized on Trump&rsquo;s lighthearted &ldquo;impeachment&rdquo; joke and FBI Director Kash Patel being in the locker room&mdash;despite Patel being in Italy to support counterterror security efforts.</p> <p>The conversation shifts to the U.S. women&rsquo;s hockey team&rsquo;s decision not to attend the State of the Union, which O&rsquo;Reilly criticizes as a political choice designed to reflect poorly on Trump. Clay and Buck agree it&rsquo;s a missed opportunity and highlight the cultural divide between the men&rsquo;s and women&rsquo;s programs. From there, the discussion turns to Gavin Newsom&rsquo;s SAT comment at a predominantly Black event&mdash;a remark that drew accusations of pandering. O&rsquo;Reilly pushes back on claims the comment was racist, argues conservatives diminish their credibility when misusing the term, and instead focuses on Newsom&rsquo;s broader weaknesses as a national candidate. He characterizes the Democratic bench for 2028 as the &ldquo;weakest field&rdquo; he&rsquo;s seen in 50 years, citing poor records, low name recognition, and an entrenched radical‑left donor network. Clay then asks whether Stephen A. Smith might enter Democratic politics; O&rsquo;Reilly suggests it&rsquo;s possible, noting Smith&rsquo;s appeal, sincerity, and ','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/933d367d-4038-427a-bd22-b3fb013b8d7c/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, guest Bill O''Reilly previews Trump''s upcoming State of the Union address, advising the president to project optimism and strength rather than dwell on the Supreme Court''s tariff ruling. The episode''s dominant thread is the cultural-political clash over the U.S. men''s hockey team''s gold-medal White House visit versus the women''s team declining a State of the Union invitation, framed as evidence the left cannot tolerate anything celebratory under Trump. The hosts also dissect Gavin Newsom''s SAT remark at a predominantly Black event and O''Reilly declares the 2028 Democratic presidential bench the ''weakest field'' in 50 years.", "key_topics": ["Trump State of the Union preview and Supreme Court tariff ruling", "U.S. Olympic hockey teams and White House culture war", "Gavin Newsom SAT controversy and 2028 Democratic presidential field", "Kash Patel''s locker-room presence and FBI politicization framing", "Stephen A. Smith as potential Democratic political figure"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The far left cannot tolerate anything celebratory occurring under Trump''s presidency \u2014 that''s what this whole hockey controversy is really about.", "speaker": "Bill O''Reilly", "context": "Frames liberal criticism of the White House hockey visit as reflexive anti-Trump partisanship rather than substantive objection, a narrative designed to delegitimize progressive cultural criticism.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "The Democratic bench for 2028 is the weakest field I''ve seen in 50 years \u2014 poor records, low name recognition, and an entrenched radical-left donor network controlling the whole thing.", "speaker": "Bill O''Reilly", "context": "Directly targets Democratic party-building efforts and attempts to pre-frame every potential 2028 contender as fatally weak or captured by the progressive donor base.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Conservatives diminish their credibility when they misuse the term racist \u2014 Newsom''s comment was pandering, not racism, and there''s a difference.", "speaker": "Bill O''Reilly", "context": "A rare cross-partisan correction pushing back on right-wing overreach, which lends O''Reilly credibility before pivoting to a broader attack on Newsom''s viability as a national candidate.", "type": "cross_partisan_signal"}], "political_attacks": ["The left is so consumed by anti-Trump hatred that it cannot allow a patriotic celebration like an Olympic gold-medal White House visit to go uncriticized", "The U.S. women''s hockey team made a deliberately political choice to snub the State of the Union in order to embarrass Trump", "Gavin Newsom is a weak panderer whose SAT remark at a Black event exposes his desperation and broader liabilities as a national figure", "The 2028 Democratic field is historically weak and controlled by a radical-left donor network that produces unelectable candidates", "Critics who attacked Kash Patel for being in the Olympic locker room ignored that he was in Italy for legitimate counterterror security work", "Media seized on Trump''s lighthearted ''impeachment'' joke to manufacture outrage"], "narrative_themes": ["The left is incapable of patriotism or celebration under a Trump presidency", "Cultural institutions (sports, media) are battlegrounds where the left enforces ideological conformity", "The Democratic Party is leaderless, weak, and captured by radical donors", "Conservative media figures are more fair-minded than liberal critics (O''Reilly correcting ''racist'' misuse)", "Trump should project optimistic strength and not be defined by court setbacks", "Gender-coded cultural divide: men''s team embraces Trump, women''s team rejects him"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode builds a durable pre-2028 frame that the entire Democratic bench is fatally weak and donor-captured, while weaponizing Olympic patriotism to paint progressives as reflexively anti-American \u2014 narratives that could suppress enthusiasm for emerging Democratic candidates and complicate progressive cultural positioning."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253454+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('f420009a39c3bc827ca48e5f7d39bf63','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 3 - Steal the Bacon!','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 20:10:00 +0000','<p>Hour 3 of the Clay Travis and Buck Sexton Show centers on a mix of political anticipation, cultural clashes, sports‑driven patriotism, and lighthearted personal storytelling as the country heads into President Trump&rsquo;s State of the Union address. Clay and Buck open the hour discussing expectations for the speech, noting prediction‑market odds that it could run more than 90 minutes. Both hosts emphasize that long speeches lose audiences and argue that Trump&mdash;despite being a natural showman&mdash;would benefit from a tighter, more powerful address that highlights major accomplishments: record‑low violent crime, a secured border, strong GDP growth, lower mortgage rates, and falling inflation. They stress that the State of the Union is one of Trump&rsquo;s rare chances to bypass media filters and speak directly to persuadable voters who may not follow daily political coverage.</p> <p>The conversation quickly turns humorous when Buck recounts the chaos of trying to track the speech while wrangling his baby and dog at home, which leads to a debate over childhood games. Buck claims &ldquo;steal the bacon&rdquo; was a universal gym‑class staple, while Clay counters with the Southern equivalent he grew up with. Listeners flood the talkback line to defend or debunk Buck&rsquo;s memories, producing a barrage of nostalgia, corrections, and hilarity&mdash;including callers from Jewish summer camps who played &ldquo;steal the salami&rdquo; and a Miami PE teacher who proudly confirms the game&rsquo;s popularity. This launches a broader discussion about modern PE, how much instruction has changed, and whether schools should rethink schedules, physical activity, and educational formats in the AI era. The two hosts consider whether America is overdue for reexamined K&ndash;6 schooling models, noting the explosion of hybrid learning pods, tutoring collectives, and parental dissatisfaction with traditional systems.</p> <p>From there, the hour circles back to politics and t','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/0f3bc305-a579-4f53-9ceb-b3fb01498664/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In Hour 3 of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, hosts Clay Travis and Buck Sexton preview Trump''s upcoming State of the Union address, arguing he should deliver a concise, accomplishment-heavy speech highlighting record-low violent crime, a secured border, strong GDP, lower mortgage rates, and falling inflation to reach persuadable voters unfiltered by media. The episode also features an extended lighthearted segment on childhood gym games and a substantive discussion on K-6 education reform, hybrid learning pods, and whether traditional schooling models are obsolete in the AI era.", "key_topics": ["Trump State of the Union strategy and messaging", "Trump administration claimed accomplishments (crime, border, GDP, inflation, mortgage rates)", "K-6 education reform and alternative schooling models in the AI era", "Media bypass strategy and direct communication with persuadable voters", "Cultural nostalgia and modern PE/schooling changes"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "This is one of Trump''s rare chances to bypass the media filters and speak directly to persuadable voters who don''t follow daily political coverage \u2014 he needs to hammer the accomplishments: record-low violent crime, secured border, strong GDP, lower mortgage rates, falling inflation.", "speaker": "Clay Travis and Buck Sexton (paraphrased consensus position)", "context": "Frames the State of the Union as a critical opportunity to cement a narrative of Trump-era success on kitchen-table issues, potentially shaping midterm positioning.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "America is overdue for a complete rethink of K-6 schooling \u2014 hybrid learning pods, tutoring collectives, parents are already voting with their feet because the traditional system is failing.", "speaker": "Clay Travis and Buck Sexton (paraphrased consensus position)", "context": "Advances a parental-rights and school-choice frame that aligns with broader conservative education policy efforts to undermine traditional public schooling.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "Long speeches lose audiences \u2014 Trump is a natural showman, but a tighter, more powerful address would be far more effective for the people he actually needs to reach.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton (paraphrased)", "context": "Rare constructive criticism of Trump''s communication style from allied media, suggesting even friendly commentators see discipline as a vulnerability.", "type": "admission"}], "political_attacks": ["Mainstream media acts as a filter that distorts Trump''s accomplishments and prevents persuadable voters from hearing his record directly", "Traditional public school systems are failing families, driving parental dissatisfaction and the rise of alternative education models", "The implication that pre-Trump conditions on crime, the border, inflation, and mortgage rates were failures attributable to Biden-era Democratic governance"], "narrative_themes": ["Trump as effective executive delivering measurable results on crime, economy, border, and inflation", "Legacy media as hostile gatekeeper that must be bypassed for truth to reach voters", "Parental rights and school choice as the future of American education", "Traditional public institutions (schools, media) as broken and in need of disruption", "Cultural nostalgia for a simpler, less regulated American childhood"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode pre-seeds a potent State of the Union narrative attributing economic and public safety gains entirely to Trump while advancing school-choice and anti-public-education framing, both of which directly threaten progressive policy priorities on public education funding and the ability to contest Trump''s economic record."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253461+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('fae0a95a25df91151cccf0c37b04e39a','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Wellness Unmasked: Breaking Big Food—How Big Tobacco Took Over America’s Food Supply','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 12:45:00 +0000','<p data-start="245" data-end="331">What if the biggest threat to your health isn&rsquo;t just what you eat&mdash;but who controls it?</p> <p data-start="333" data-end="568">On this episode of <em data-start="352" data-end="371">Wellness Unmasked</em>, Dr. Nicole Saphier sits down with filmmakers Patrick and Ashley Sullivan, creators of the new documentary <em data-start="479" data-end="567">Breaking Big Food: How the American Food System Went Rotten&mdash;and How It&rsquo;s Being Revived</em>.</p> <p data-start="570" data-end="973">After a personal health scare, the Sullivans set out to uncover the truth behind America&rsquo;s food industry&mdash;and what they found is shocking. From Big Tobacco quietly acquiring major food companies in the 1980s and 90s, to the explosion of ultra-processed foods and thousands of &ldquo;generally recognized as safe&rdquo; (GRAS) chemicals in our food supply, this conversation pulls back the curtain on how we got here.</p> <p data-start="975" data-end="996">They also break down:</p> <ul data-start="997" data-end="1508"> <li data-start="997" data-end="1058"> <p data-start="999" data-end="1058">The hidden history of Big Tobacco&rsquo;s influence on Big Food</p> </li> <li data-start="1059" data-end="1129"> <p data-start="1061" data-end="1129">Why U.S. food standards differ dramatically from Europe and Canada</p> </li> <li data-start="1130" data-end="1199"> <p data-start="1132" data-end="1199">The rise of seed oils, additives, and ultra-processed ingredients</p> </li> <li data-start="1200" data-end="1268"> <p data-start="1202" data-end="1268">The truth about glyphosate, pesticides, and regulatory loopholes</p> </li> <li data-start="1269" data-end="1346"> <p data-start="1271" data-end="1346">Surprising sources of toxins&mdash;including coffee and everyday &ldquo;health foods&rdquo;</p> </li> <li data-start="1347" data-end="1423"> <p data-start="1349" data-end="1423">Simple, practical tips to avoid harmful ingredients at the grocery store<','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/563445b4-4751-41e2-b7b9-b2cd0152670e/fa3bb8a8-194b-402f-a5da-b3fa017330a6/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On this episode of the Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show''s ''Wellness Unmasked'' segment, Dr. Nicole Saphier interviews filmmakers Patrick and Ashley Sullivan about their documentary ''Breaking Big Food,'' which argues that Big Tobacco''s acquisition of major food companies in the 1980s-90s led to the explosion of ultra-processed foods, harmful additives, and lax regulatory standards in the American food supply. The episode frames U.S. food regulation as fundamentally compromised by corporate capture and regulatory loopholes, contrasting American standards unfavorably with Europe and Canada.", "key_topics": ["Big Tobacco''s historical takeover of major food companies", "Ultra-processed foods, seed oils, GRAS chemicals, and glyphosate in the U.S. food supply", "Regulatory failures and U.S. vs. European/Canadian food safety standards", "Personal health and practical consumer strategies to avoid harmful ingredients"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Big Tobacco quietly acquired major food companies in the 1980s and 90s, and they brought the same playbook \u2014 engineer addiction, obscure the science, and capture the regulators.", "speaker": "Patrick or Ashley Sullivan (filmmakers)", "context": "Frames the American food crisis as a deliberate corporate conspiracy with roots in tobacco industry tactics, a narrative that could fuel both right-populist and left-progressive regulatory arguments.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "There are thousands of chemicals in our food that are ''generally recognized as safe'' that have never been independently tested \u2014 and many of them are banned in Europe and Canada.", "speaker": "Patrick or Ashley Sullivan (filmmakers)", "context": "Directly indicts the FDA''s GRAS framework and positions U.S. regulatory agencies as failing American consumers, a theme that aligns with MAHA (Make America Healthy Again) and RFK Jr.''s agenda.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "The biggest threat to your health isn''t just what you eat \u2014 it''s who controls it.", "speaker": "Episode framing / Dr. Nicole Saphier", "context": "Encapsulates the populist anti-corporate framing that bridges right-wing distrust of government agencies with health freedom messaging.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Implicit attack on the FDA and federal food regulators for allowing thousands of untested GRAS chemicals into the food supply while Europe and Canada ban them", "Framing of the regulatory state as captured by corporate interests \u2014 specifically Big Tobacco and Big Food \u2014 rather than protecting public health", "Implicit critique of decades of bipartisan regulatory failure, though the populist-right framing aligns with MAHA/RFK Jr. skepticism of federal health agencies"], "narrative_themes": ["Corporate capture of government regulators (FDA, USDA)", "American health crisis driven by deliberate corporate engineering of addictive processed foods", "U.S. exceptionalism in the negative \u2014 America''s food standards are worse than peer nations", "MAHA-adjacent health populism: elites and corporations are poisoning ordinary Americans", "Individual empowerment and personal responsibility as the solution to systemic food industry corruption", "Distrust of ''generally recognized as safe'' regulatory frameworks and institutional science"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "This episode advances the MAHA/RFK Jr. health-populist narrative on a major right-wing platform, building cross-partisan appeal around food safety concerns that could undermine progressive defenses of federal regulatory agencies like the FDA while bolstering the Trump administration''s rationale for restructuring or defunding those agencies."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253466+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('73b68f2aaa06ee2e83d65c84aa2e0c1b','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Normally Podcast: Olympic Gold Pride, Newsom’s “I Can’t Read” Act, and NYC Subway Chaos','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 09:00:00 +0000','<p data-start="529" data-end="781">On this episode of <em data-start="548" data-end="558">Normally</em>, Mary Katharine Ham and Karol Markowicz react to a disturbing security incident at Mar-a-Lago and the broader pattern of escalating threats against public officials&mdash;stories that vanish from the headlines far too quickly.</p> <p data-start="783" data-end="1295">Then it&rsquo;s time for a much-needed palate cleanser: <strong data-start="833" data-end="870">Team USA&rsquo;s Olympic hockey triumph</strong>, with both the men&rsquo;s and women&rsquo;s teams winning gold in overtime against Canada. Mary Katharine and Karol break down the gritty, emotional win&mdash;complete with missing teeth, family legacy, and the powerful tribute to fallen NHL star <strong data-start="1101" data-end="1120">Johnny Gaudreau</strong> and his family that had fans tearing up worldwide. Plus: the small controversy over Kash Patel celebrating with the team&hellip; and why most normal people don&rsquo;t care.</p> <p data-start="1297" data-end="1723">From there, the hosts turn to <strong data-start="1327" data-end="1380">Gavin Newsom&rsquo;s latest &ldquo;I&rsquo;m just like you&rdquo; routine</strong>, including the eyebrow-raising &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t read&rdquo;/SAT score messaging and what it signals about his larger political rebrand&mdash;and media protection. They also dig into <strong data-start="1543" data-end="1609">Bernie Sanders&rsquo; inability to answer a basic follow-up question</strong> about why the U.S. produces more successful businesses than Europe, and why &ldquo;tax the billionaires&rdquo; is not a plan.</p> <p data-start="1725" data-end="2016">Finally, <em data-start="1734" data-end="1744">Normally</em> tackles the viral New York City debate no one should have to have: <strong data-start="1812" data-end="1881">is urinating on a crowded subway car just part of urban life now?</strong> The hosts explain why &ldquo;stop noticing&rdquo; isn&rsquo;t governance, and why','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/7458e54b-1395-49ad-b2a5-b1f000dea830/2941a757-0f21-4ab0-9439-b3fb003763d9/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On this episode of the ''Normally'' podcast (part of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show), guests Mary Katharine Ham and Karol Markowicz cover a Mar-a-Lago security incident and escalating threats against public officials, celebrate Team USA''s double Olympic hockey gold over Canada, mock Gavin Newsom''s populist rebrand including his ''I can''t read'' SAT score messaging, criticize Bernie Sanders for failing to explain why the U.S. outperforms Europe in business creation, and highlight viral footage of public urination on a NYC subway as evidence of progressive governance failure.", "key_topics": ["Mar-a-Lago security incident and threats against public officials", "Team USA Olympic hockey gold and Kash Patel celebration controversy", "Gavin Newsom''s populist rebrand and media protection", "Bernie Sanders'' inability to defend anti-billionaire economic messaging", "NYC subway disorder as progressive governance failure"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Gavin Newsom is out there doing his ''I can''t read, I''m just like you'' routine with the SAT scores, and the media is helping him build this blue-collar rebrand instead of asking why the governor of the largest state is bragging about being uninformed.", "speaker": "Mary Katharine Ham (paraphrased from episode description)", "context": "Frames Newsom''s 2028 positioning as fundamentally dishonest and media-assisted, a key attack line against his anticipated presidential run.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Bernie Sanders can''t answer a simple follow-up about why the United States produces more successful businesses than Europe. ''Tax the billionaires'' is not a plan \u2014 it''s a bumper sticker.", "speaker": "Mary Katharine Ham and/or Karol Markowicz (paraphrased from episode description)", "context": "Directly undermines Sanders'' credibility as an economic voice and frames progressive taxation arguments as intellectually empty.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Someone urinating on a crowded subway car is not just ''part of urban life'' \u2014 ''stop noticing'' isn''t governance, and the fact that we even have to debate this tells you everything about where progressive leadership has taken New York City.", "speaker": "Mary Katharine Ham and/or Karol Markowicz (paraphrased from episode description)", "context": "Encapsulates the right''s quality-of-life framing against progressive city governance, designed to resonate with suburban and moderate voters.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Gavin Newsom is executing a fake populist rebrand with his ''I can''t read''/low SAT score messaging, aided by compliant media that won''t scrutinize his record as California governor", "Bernie Sanders cannot defend his own economic worldview when pressed on why U.S. capitalism outperforms European social democracies \u2014 ''tax the billionaires'' is a slogan, not a policy", "NYC progressive leadership has normalized public disorder including public urination on subways, and tells residents to ''stop noticing'' rather than enforcing basic public order", "Media suppresses and quickly drops stories about security threats and violence targeting Republican/conservative public officials, including the Mar-a-Lago incident", "Criticism of those upset about Kash Patel celebrating with Team USA hockey is framed as out-of-touch outrage that ''normal people don''t care about''"], "narrative_themes": ["Progressive governance produces visible urban decay and disorder", "Democratic presidential aspirants rely on media protection and dishonest populist cosplay", "Left-wing economic arguments collapse under basic scrutiny", "Violence and threats against conservatives are underreported by mainstream media", "Liberal media outrage is disconnected from what ''normal people'' actually care about", "American patriotism and national pride are conservative-coded values"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode builds durable anti-Newsom 2028 framing, reinforces quality-of-life attacks on progressive urban governance that resonate with swing voters, and effectively portrays Sanders-style economics as intellectually bankrupt \u2014 all narratives with crossover appeal beyond the conservative base."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253471+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('06a7a73a93bcc1106d981e5eee51d3e0','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Daily Review with Clay and Buck - Feb 23 2026','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:25:00 +0000','<p><strong>Team USA</strong></p> <p>Buck celebrates Team USA&rsquo;s historic Olympic triumph in men&rsquo;s ice hockey, defeating Canada to win the gold medal for the first time since 1980. He plays audio from star player Jack Hughes, whose comments about loving the United States set the patriotic vibe of the hour. Buck brings in the show&rsquo;s two hockey‑obsessed producers to offer expert commentary, recap the game, and revel in both the men''s and women&rsquo;s U.S. hockey teams winning gold. The crew recalls fan reactions and the cultural significance of a rare Olympic sweep over Canada in a sport the Canadians are known to dominate.</p> <p><strong>Cost of Illegal Immigration&nbsp;</strong></p> <p>President Trump&rsquo;s Angel Families remembrance event at the White House. Buck opens the hour by describing the ceremony honoring families whose loved ones were killed by individuals in the country illegally, highlighting Trump&rsquo;s commitment to giving these families a national voice despite media outlets and Democratic politicians who routinely downplay or ignore the connection between illegal immigration and violent crime. Buck explains how political rhetoric has shifted from referring to &ldquo;illegal aliens&rdquo; to softer, euphemistic terms like &ldquo;undocumented immigrants,&rdquo; which he argues is intentional linguistic manipulation designed to weaken border‑security arguments.</p> <p>Buck plays and analyzes Trump&rsquo;s remarks, including his criticism of politicians who prioritize the comfort of foreign criminals over the safety of American citizens. Trump tells the families that their pain has been censored and suppressed for political purposes, and Buck emphasizes that mainstream media has long focused exclusively on sympathetic narratives about DREAMers while burying the far more numerous cases involving repeat‑offender illegal immigrants responsible for homicide, DUIs, assaults, and other serious crimes. Buck revisits the longstanding politic','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/4c3043cb-8e74-4946-8b68-b3fa01486710/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this episode of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, Buck Sexton leads a celebration of Team USA''s men''s and women''s ice hockey gold medals at the 2026 Olympics, framing them as patriotic triumphs over Canada. The episode then pivots to extensive coverage of President Trump''s Angel Families remembrance ceremony at the White House, with Buck arguing that Democrats and mainstream media systematically suppress stories of violent crimes committed by illegal immigrants while promoting sympathetic narratives about DREAMers, and criticizing the linguistic shift from ''illegal aliens'' to ''undocumented immigrants'' as deliberate political manipulation.", "key_topics": ["2026 Winter Olympics - Team USA hockey gold medals", "Trump''s Angel Families White House ceremony and illegal immigration rhetoric", "Media and Democratic framing of immigration language and crime"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The mainstream media has long focused exclusively on sympathetic narratives about DREAMers while burying the far more numerous cases involving repeat-offender illegal immigrants responsible for homicide, DUIs, assaults, and other serious crimes.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton frames media coverage of immigration as a deliberate suppression campaign, positioning the Angel Families event as a corrective to institutional bias.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Politicians prioritize the comfort of foreign criminals over the safety of American citizens... your pain has been censored and suppressed for political purposes.", "speaker": "President Trump (as played/quoted by Buck Sexton)", "context": "Trump''s remarks at the Angel Families event directly accuse Democratic politicians of complicity in violence against Americans, a framing designed to emotionally anchor immigration enforcement to victim narratives.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "The shift from ''illegal aliens'' to ''undocumented immigrants'' is intentional linguistic manipulation designed to weaken border-security arguments.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton attacks progressive language norms around immigration as a deliberate strategic tactic, seeking to delegitimize inclusive terminology used by Democrats and most mainstream outlets.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Democrats and media accused of systematically censoring and suppressing Angel Families'' stories to protect a pro-immigration political agenda", "Democratic politicians accused of prioritizing the comfort of ''foreign criminals'' over the safety of American citizens", "Mainstream media accused of exclusively promoting sympathetic DREAMer narratives while burying cases of violent crimes by illegal immigrants", "Progressives accused of deliberate linguistic manipulation by shifting from ''illegal aliens'' to ''undocumented immigrants'' to undermine border-security arguments"], "narrative_themes": ["Patriotic nationalism amplified through Olympic sports victories", "Illegal immigration as an existential public safety threat to American families", "Media and Democrats as complicit in covering up immigrant crime", "Language policing as a progressive weapon against border enforcement", "Trump as champion and voice for forgotten American victims"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "The episode pairs emotionally potent victim narratives with a systematic delegitimization of progressive immigration framing, media credibility, and inclusive language norms \u2014 all reinforced by a White House event designed to build sustained public support for aggressive enforcement policies and to pre-empt Democratic opposition as morally complicit in violent crime."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253482+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('01e38f27075045d7a28c570593e2b9a4','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 1 - Bring Back Old School Books!','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:20:00 +0000','<p>Hour 1 of the Clay Travis and Buck Sexton Show opens with Buck hosting solo while Clay is out, and the program immediately dives into a packed news cycle. The hour begins with international coverage as Buck explains rising tensions in Mexico after a major cartel leader was killed during a joint U.S.&ndash;Mexico operation. He emphasizes that the cartel conflict is escalating and sets the stage for deeper analysis later in the program.</p> <p>The tone quickly shifts to a patriotic highlight as Buck celebrates Team USA&rsquo;s historic Olympic triumph in men&rsquo;s ice hockey, defeating Canada to win the gold medal for the first time since 1980. He plays audio from star player Jack Hughes, whose comments about loving the United States set the patriotic vibe of the hour. Buck brings in the show&rsquo;s two hockey‑obsessed producers to offer expert commentary, recap the game, and revel in both the men''s and women&rsquo;s U.S. hockey teams winning gold. The crew recalls fan reactions and the cultural significance of a rare Olympic sweep over Canada in a sport the Canadians are known to dominate.</p> <p>The hour then pivots sharply to breaking domestic news: an armed intruder was shot and killed at Mar‑a‑Lago after reportedly scaling a fence while carrying a shotgun and gasoline. Buck notes that the president was not present at the time but expresses deep frustration at the escalating pattern of assassination attempts and threats against President Trump. He recounts how Trump has survived previous attempts, including being shot in the ear in a prior incident, and highlights that the press does not give enough attention to the bravery, composure, and risk Trump continues to face. Buck also warns that the country should expect continued threats and urges listeners to &ldquo;say a prayer&rdquo; for the president and those responsible for his protection.</p> <p>Buck transitions to a lighter segment celebrating sports moments from the past year, including Indiana Universit','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/622af2f3-5868-423a-be07-b3fa013a15dd/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this solo-hosted episode of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, Buck Sexton covers a packed news cycle including the killing of a cartel leader in a joint U.S.-Mexico operation, Team USA''s historic Olympic hockey gold medal sweep, and a breaking security incident at Mar-a-Lago where an armed intruder carrying a shotgun and gasoline was shot and killed after scaling a fence. Buck frames the Mar-a-Lago breach as part of an escalating pattern of assassination attempts against President Trump and criticizes the press for insufficient coverage of the dangers Trump faces.", "key_topics": ["Mar-a-Lago armed intruder and Trump assassination threat pattern", "U.S.-Mexico cartel operations and escalating border/cartel conflict", "Team USA Olympic hockey gold medal victory over Canada"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The press does not give enough attention to the bravery, composure, and risk that President Trump continues to face. This man has been shot in the ear, and now someone scales a fence at Mar-a-Lago with a shotgun and gasoline.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton frames media coverage of threats against Trump as deliberately insufficient, reinforcing a narrative of media bias and Trump as a uniquely persecuted figure.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Say a prayer for the president and for those responsible for his protection \u2014 this country should expect continued threats.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton elevates Trump''s physical security into a quasi-spiritual rallying point for the conservative base, implying an ongoing existential threat environment.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "Jack Hughes talking about how much he loves the United States \u2014 that''s the kind of patriotism we need more of in this country.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton uses Olympic athlete Jack Hughes''s pro-American comments to set a patriotic frame that implicitly contrasts with left-leaning cultural critiques of American identity.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["The mainstream press deliberately underplays assassination attempts and security threats against President Trump, revealing systemic anti-Trump media bias", "Implicit criticism that the left and media lack the patriotic spirit demonstrated by Team USA hockey players who express unqualified love for the country"], "narrative_themes": ["Trump as a uniquely persecuted and courageous leader under constant physical threat", "Media bias and deliberate suppression of stories sympathetic to Trump", "Muscular patriotism and American exceptionalism through sports", "Escalating cartel threat requiring aggressive U.S. military/law enforcement action", "The security state must do more to protect conservative leaders"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode builds a potent narrative of Trump as a martyred figure facing ongoing assassination threats while the press looks away, which could energize the base around security-state expansion and delegitimize media criticism of Trump; the cartel framing also reinforces hawkish border policy momentum."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253487+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('66583f69a52cab3a2168f53bcb8bf1ab','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 2 - Cost of Illegal Immigration','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:15:00 +0000','<p>Hour 2 of the Clay Travis and Buck Sexton Show focuses heavily on immigration, cartel violence, national security, and the human cost of illegal immigration, anchored by President Trump&rsquo;s Angel Families remembrance event at the White House. Buck opens the hour by describing the ceremony honoring families whose loved ones were killed by individuals in the country illegally, highlighting Trump&rsquo;s commitment to giving these families a national voice despite media outlets and Democratic politicians who routinely downplay or ignore the connection between illegal immigration and violent crime. Buck explains how political rhetoric has shifted from referring to &ldquo;illegal aliens&rdquo; to softer, euphemistic terms like &ldquo;undocumented immigrants,&rdquo; which he argues is intentional linguistic manipulation designed to weaken border‑security arguments.</p> <p>Buck plays and analyzes Trump&rsquo;s remarks, including his criticism of politicians who prioritize the comfort of foreign criminals over the safety of American citizens. Trump tells the families that their pain has been censored and suppressed for political purposes, and Buck emphasizes that mainstream media has long focused exclusively on sympathetic narratives about DREAMers while burying the far more numerous cases involving repeat‑offender illegal immigrants responsible for homicide, DUIs, assaults, and other serious crimes. Buck revisits the longstanding political debate around illegal immigration, arguing that many immigration advocates refuse to admit any downsides at all&mdash;and that Trump, unlike his predecessors, is openly confronting the reality of violent crimes committed by those who should not be in the country.</p> <p>The discussion expands into broader immigration policy history, including failures by both Republican and Democratic administrations, the border surge under Biden, and the strain illegal immigration places on city budgets, social‑service systems, and local communit','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/f6c50dd7-e0aa-4b8a-a587-b3fa013a15de/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "Hour 2 of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show centers on Trump''s Angel Families remembrance event at the White House, with Buck Sexton arguing that mainstream media and Democratic politicians systematically suppress stories of violent crimes committed by undocumented immigrants. The hosts frame the immigration debate as a choice between protecting American citizens and shielding ''foreign criminals,'' while attacking Biden-era border policy, Democratic linguistic shifts around immigration terminology, and media focus on DREAMer narratives.", "key_topics": ["Angel Families and violent crimes committed by undocumented immigrants", "Trump White House immigration messaging and remembrance ceremony", "Media and Democratic framing of immigration terminology (illegal aliens vs. undocumented immigrants)", "Biden-era border surge and strain on city budgets and social services", "Cartel violence and national security"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The mainstream media has long focused exclusively on sympathetic narratives about DREAMers while burying the far more numerous cases involving repeat-offender illegal immigrants responsible for homicide, DUIs, assaults, and other serious crimes.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Directly accuses mainstream media of suppressing crime-related immigration stories, setting up a counter-narrative to progressive immigration framing.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "The shift from ''illegal aliens'' to ''undocumented immigrants'' is intentional linguistic manipulation designed to weaken border-security arguments.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Frames progressive language evolution on immigration as a deliberate propaganda strategy, reinforcing right-wing pushback against inclusive terminology.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Your pain has been censored and suppressed for political purposes \u2014 politicians prioritize the comfort of foreign criminals over the safety of American citizens.", "speaker": "Donald Trump (as played/quoted by hosts)", "context": "Trump''s direct address to Angel Families positions Democrats and media as complicit in covering up immigrant-linked violence, a potent emotional appeal being amplified to millions of listeners.", "type": "attack"}], "political_attacks": ["Democrats and mainstream media deliberately suppress and censor stories of Americans killed by illegal immigrants to protect their open-borders agenda", "Democratic politicians prioritize the comfort of ''foreign criminals'' over the safety of American citizens", "Biden administration''s border policies caused an unprecedented surge of illegal immigration that has strained city budgets, social services, and local communities", "Immigration advocates refuse to admit any downsides of illegal immigration whatsoever", "Progressive media exclusively platforms sympathetic DREAMer stories while burying cases of repeat-offender illegal immigrants committing violent crimes"], "narrative_themes": ["American victims silenced by a complicit media-political establishment", "Linguistic manipulation by the left to soften public perception of illegal immigration", "Democrats choosing illegal immigrants over American citizens'' safety", "Trump as the singular political figure willing to confront uncomfortable truths about immigration", "Systemic failure of both parties on immigration, but Democrats are uniquely culpable for the current crisis", "The human cost of illegal immigration as the primary lens for policy debate"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "This episode amplifies the White House''s most emotionally potent immigration messaging \u2014 Angel Families \u2014 to a massive right-leaning audience, directly framing progressive immigration positions as complicity in violent crime, which could drive public opinion against comprehensive immigration reform, DACA protections, and asylum policy while pressuring moderate Democrats to distance themselves from inclusive immigration language."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253491+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('9f0e2fff50831cfad30a989bd7d4016d','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Hour 3 - Let Him Cook','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:10:00 +0000','<p>Hour 3 opens with Buck Sexton solo‑hosting and hitting rapid‑fire headlines before a deeper dive into law, national security, and 2026 election politics. He leads with a patriotic recap of Team USA&rsquo;s Olympic men&rsquo;s hockey gold, praising Jack Hughes and the grit of a player who finished the game with a broken front tooth&mdash;framing the win as a unifying, USA‑first sports moment. From there, the tone shifts to security: Buck details the armed intruder shot and killed at Mar‑a‑Lago, emphasizing the persistent, elevated threats against President Trump and crediting the Secret Service&rsquo;s swift response.</p> <p>Buck then revisits the Supreme Court&rsquo;s tariff ruling from the prior week, explaining how the Court said the president could not use IEEPA to raise tariff revenue, prompting Trump to pivot immediately to other legal authorities. He outlines Trump&rsquo;s response: a temporary global tariff under Section 122 of the Trade Act of 1974 (10% and then 15%) and continued enforcement via existing Section 232 and Section 301 measures. The discussion highlights Treasury Secretary Scott Besson&rsquo;s defense of the program&mdash;arguing tariffs have helped rebalance trade, reduce the goods deficit, and catalyze factory reshoring&mdash;while Buck notes the broader economy&rsquo;s resilience despite dire predictions from establishment economists.</p> <p>Staying on national security, Buck tracks breaking developments in the war on cartels. After reviewing the weekend operation that killed a top Jalisco New Generation Cartel (CJNG) boss with a $15 million bounty, he reports a same‑day kinetic strike destroying a narco‑terrorist boat in the Caribbean, with no U.S. casualties. He describes CJNG as a hybrid criminal‑terrorist organization driving fentanyl trafficking into U.S. cities and warns that, under Trump, expect more direct and persistent counter‑cartel action&mdash;covert and overt&mdash;to disrupt supply chains that fuel overdoses, gang violence,','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/f67fb538-6b52-4a52-8d59-b3fa014996b6/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this solo-hosted hour of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, Buck Sexton covers Team USA''s Olympic hockey gold as a patriotic unifier, the armed intruder killed at Mar-a-Lago, Trump''s legal pivot on tariffs after the Supreme Court''s IEEPA ruling, and escalating kinetic military operations against Mexican drug cartels. The episode frames Trump as effectively adapting to legal setbacks, delivering economic resilience through tariffs, and aggressively prosecuting a war on cartels that prior administrations neglected.", "key_topics": ["Trump tariff strategy post-Supreme Court IEEPA ruling", "Military and covert operations against Jalisco New Generation Cartel (CJNG)", "Mar-a-Lago armed intruder and ongoing threats to Trump", "Treasury Secretary Scott Besson''s defense of tariff-driven reshoring", "Team USA Olympic hockey gold as patriotic narrative"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "The Supreme Court said Trump couldn''t use IEEPA for tariff revenue, and within hours he pivoted to Section 122 of the Trade Act of 1974 \u2014 10 percent, then 15 percent \u2014 plus the existing 232 and 301 authorities. The establishment said tariffs would crash the economy. They were wrong. The economy is resilient and factories are reshoring.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Frames the SCOTUS loss as a minor procedural speed bump rather than a constitutional rebuke, and positions establishment economists as discredited critics.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Under Trump, expect more direct and persistent counter-cartel action \u2014 covert and overt \u2014 to disrupt the supply chains that fuel overdoses and gang violence in American cities. CJNG is a hybrid criminal-terrorist organization and we''re treating them like one.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Normalizes and champions extrajudicial military strikes against cartels on foreign soil, building public support for an expanded kinetic posture with minimal legal scrutiny.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "The dire predictions from establishment economists about tariffs collapsing the economy \u2014 none of it materialized. Treasury Secretary Besson is right: the goods deficit is shrinking and factories are coming back.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Elevates Scott Besson as a credible economic voice while discrediting mainstream economic consensus, reinforcing a populist-protectionist frame ahead of 2026 midterms.", "type": "claim"}], "political_attacks": ["Establishment economists and media pundits were dead wrong about tariffs crashing the economy \u2014 their predictions are discredited", "Previous administrations (implicitly Biden/Obama) failed to take direct military action against cartels like CJNG, allowing fentanyl to flood American cities", "Critics of Trump''s tariff authority are procedural obstructionists \u2014 Trump simply pivots to other legal tools and keeps winning"], "narrative_themes": ["Trump as adaptive executive who outmaneuvers legal constraints through alternative statutory authorities", "Tariffs as economic success story: reshoring, deficit reduction, elite economists proven wrong", "Cartels as terrorist organizations justifying military-grade kinetic operations", "Persistent physical threats against Trump reinforce his status as a besieged but resilient leader", "Patriotic sports moments as cultural unifiers that reinforce ''USA-first'' identity", "The ''let him cook'' frame: give Trump operational latitude and results will follow"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "This episode builds broad public legitimacy for unilateral executive war-making against cartels, normalizes tariff escalation through statutory workarounds after a Supreme Court check, and frames progressive/establishment opposition as both incompetent and obstructionist \u2014 all potent narratives heading into 2026 midterms that undercut progressive positions on trade, civil liberties, and foreign policy restraint."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253497+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('c6860a191efce2c43bce38fbe37f664b','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','It''s a Numbers Game: The Numbers Behind America’s Transgender Debate: New Polls Reveal a Growing Political Divide','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 14:45:00 +0000','<p>On this episode of A Numbers Game, Ryan Girdusky breaks down the latest polling data shaking up the political landscape&mdash;and exposing deep divisions within the Democratic coalition and the broader American public. Drawing on a national survey of over 3,000 registered voters, Ryan walks through the numbers on key transgender-related policies, including youth medical treatments, school sports participation, and bathroom access laws.</p> <p>The data tells a striking story: while Republican voters remain largely unified, Democratic voters are increasingly split&mdash;raising serious questions about messaging, priorities, and the future of the culture war. Ryan explores why public opinion appears to be shifting, how activists and media figures are responding to inconvenient data, and what this means for upcoming elections.</p> <p>Plus, Ryan offers a strategic warning to Republicans: even when the numbers are on your side, winning campaigns require more than a single issue. From polling insights to political strategy, this episode delivers a data-driven look at one of the most contentious debates in America today.</p> <p><a href="mailto:ryan@numbersgamepodcast.com">EMAIL RYAN</a></p><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck" rel="payment">Follow Clay & Buck on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck</a></p><p>See <a href="https://omnystudio.com/listener">omnystudio.com/listener</a> for privacy information.</p>','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/f89d9034-241d-480e-a101-b252011f76ce/910eebeb-6609-49f0-9f7d-b3f900fc938e/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On this episode of ''A Numbers Game,'' hosted under the Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show umbrella, guest analyst Ryan Girdusky presents polling data from a 3,000+ registered voter survey on transgender-related policies \u2014 including youth medical treatments, school sports participation, and bathroom access. Girdusky argues the data reveals a unified Republican electorate and a fracturing Democratic coalition on these cultural issues, while cautioning Republicans that favorable polling on a single wedge issue is insufficient to win elections.", "key_topics": ["Polling on transgender-related policies (youth medical treatments, sports, bathrooms)", "Democratic coalition fractures on cultural issues", "Republican electoral strategy and limits of single-issue culture war campaigns"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Democratic voters are increasingly split on these transgender policies \u2014 the coalition is fracturing, and the data makes that undeniable.", "speaker": "Ryan Girdusky", "context": "Frames the Democratic Party as internally divided on a high-salience culture war issue, a narrative designed to suppress progressive unity and embolden Republican wedge campaigns.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Activists and media figures are responding to inconvenient data by ignoring it or attacking the messenger \u2014 but the numbers don''t lie.", "speaker": "Ryan Girdusky", "context": "Positions progressive advocates and allied media as anti-empirical and in denial, undermining their credibility on transgender rights messaging.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Even when the numbers are on your side, Republicans need to understand that winning campaigns require more than a single issue.", "speaker": "Ryan Girdusky", "context": "A strategically notable admission that over-reliance on anti-trans messaging could backfire for the GOP, suggesting awareness of the 2022-2024 lesson that culture war saturation has diminishing returns.", "type": "admission"}], "political_attacks": ["Democrats are portrayed as a fractured coalition unable to hold a unified position on transgender policies, suggesting internal weakness", "Progressive activists and allied media are accused of ignoring or suppressing polling data that contradicts their advocacy on transgender rights", "The broader Democratic messaging apparatus is framed as out of touch with the majority of registered voters, including their own base, on youth medical treatments and school sports participation"], "narrative_themes": ["Parental rights and child protection as majority-consensus positions", "Democratic coalition fragility on cultural issues", "Data-driven populism vs. elite progressive activism", "Culture war as electoral wedge \u2014 powerful but insufficient alone", "Media and activist class as insulated from public opinion"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "This episode provides a sophisticated, data-wrapped framework for exploiting intra-Democratic divisions on transgender rights \u2014 one of the right''s most potent wedge issues \u2014 and its distribution through a major conservative media platform gives it significant reach and credibility with Republican operatives and voters heading into election cycles."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253502+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('312caac52214917e4c8698e8978235a2','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','David Rutherford Show: Colorado’s Elections Were Stolen? Joe Oltmann Lays Out the Case','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 13:00:00 +0000','<p data-start="1390" data-end="1551">Joe Oltmann joins David Rutherford for a powerful conversation on election integrity, NGOs, judicial accountability, and his campaign for Governor of Colorado.</p> <p data-start="1553" data-end="1889">In this episode, Oltmann outlines his claims about Dominion Voting Systems, nonprofit funding networks, and what he believes is a long-running infrastructure influencing American elections. He also discusses the case of Tina Peters, qualified immunity for judges, and why he believes local action is the key to restoring accountability.</p> <p data-start="1891" data-end="2032">Whether you agree or disagree, this episode dives deep into the arguments shaping one of the most heated debates in modern American politics.<br><br>Sponsors: Black Rifle Coffee: <a href="https://www.blackriflecoffee.com/">https://www.blackriflecoffee.com/</a> <br><br>Next Steps: - 🏫 Get coaching by David Rutherford: https://www.froglogicinstitute.com/ - 📕 Get David''s novel, The Poet Warrior: https://www.ballastbooks.com/ballast-bookstore/the-poet-warrior - 📰 Sign up for David''s weekly newsletter for free coaching tips, updates, and more: <a href="https://davidrutherfordletter.substack.com/">https://davidrutherfordletter.substack.com/</a></p><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck" rel="payment">Follow Clay & Buck on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck</a></p><p>See <a href="https://omnystudio.com/listener">omnystudio.com/listener</a> for privacy information.</p>','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/288b578c-49f1-4136-a9bf-b2b101268489/b0f84661-b2f8-4155-800f-b3fa00d095b7/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On the Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show platform, guest host David Rutherford interviews Joe Oltmann \u2014 a Colorado gubernatorial candidate and prominent election denial activist \u2014 who lays out conspiracy claims about Dominion Voting Systems, nonprofit funding networks, and alleged systematic election theft in Colorado. The episode promotes Oltmann''s narrative that a coordinated infrastructure of NGOs, judges, and voting technology companies has corrupted American elections, while also platforming his campaign for Governor of Colorado and advocating for the removal of qualified immunity for judges.", "key_topics": ["Election denial and Dominion Voting Systems conspiracy theories", "Joe Oltmann''s 2026 Colorado gubernatorial campaign", "Nonprofit and NGO influence on elections", "Tina Peters case and judicial accountability", "Qualified immunity reform for judges", "Local political action as strategy for right-wing movement"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Colorado''s elections were stolen through a long-running infrastructure of NGOs, nonprofits, and Dominion Voting Systems working together to influence outcomes.", "speaker": "Joe Oltmann", "context": "Oltmann presents debunked Dominion conspiracy theories as established fact while running for governor, giving these claims a campaign-level platform.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Tina Peters was persecuted by a judicial system that protects itself through qualified immunity \u2014 judges should be held personally accountable.", "speaker": "Joe Oltmann", "context": "Oltmann reframes the conviction of Tina Peters \u2014 who was found guilty of tampering with election equipment \u2014 as political persecution, while advocating for stripping judicial protections.", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "The key to restoring accountability is local action \u2014 taking back school boards, county offices, and state government from the inside.", "speaker": "Joe Oltmann", "context": "Signals a strategic focus on down-ballot infiltration that mirrors broader right-wing efforts to control local government infrastructure.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Dominion Voting Systems accused of being part of a coordinated election-stealing infrastructure", "NGOs and nonprofit organizations framed as covert operatives corrupting American elections", "Colorado''s judicial system attacked as self-protecting and complicit in political persecution of election integrity activists like Tina Peters", "Implicit attack on Colorado''s Democratic political establishment as beneficiaries of allegedly stolen elections", "Judges broadly attacked as unaccountable actors shielded by qualified immunity"], "narrative_themes": ["Systemic election fraud as an article of faith requiring no new evidence", "Political martyrdom of election deniers (Tina Peters as persecuted truth-teller)", "Deep state extends to state-level judiciary and nonprofit sector", "Local government capture as the path to right-wing restoration", "Elite institutional corruption vs. grassroots populist accountability", "Qualified immunity as a tool of judicial self-protection against the people"], "threat_level": "high", "threat_rationale": "This episode platforms a gubernatorial candidate actively promoting debunked election fraud conspiracies on a major national conservative media outlet, normalizing election denialism as a campaign platform while advocating for dismantling judicial independence and systematizing right-wing capture of local government \u2014 all of which pose direct threats to democratic institutions and progressive governance in a swing-trending state."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253506+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('d1beb9125f52e571a2245d3486898868','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','The Tudor Dixon Podcast: Exposing the Over-Sexualization of Kids in Dance','Mon, 23 Feb 2026 09:00:00 +0000','<p data-start="287" data-end="457">On this episode of <em data-start="306" data-end="331">The Tudor Dixon Podcast</em>, Tudor tackles a growing concern for parents across America: the over-sexualization of children in dance and on social media.</p> <p data-start="459" data-end="885">Joined by dance educator and <em data-start="488" data-end="525">Dance Awareness: No Child Exploited</em> founder Mary Bawden, Tudor explores how a once wholesome activity has shifted toward hyper-sexualized performances, influenced by media, internet culture, and social platforms like TikTok. Together, they break down the difference between healthy and harmful dance, how predators exploit online content, and what parents need to know to protect their children.</p> <p data-start="887" data-end="1089">From &ldquo;sharenting&rdquo; to the rise of &ldquo;thirst traps&rdquo; among teens, this conversation reveals the hidden dangers facing kids today&mdash;and offers practical tools to help families make safer, more informed choices.</p><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck" rel="payment">Follow Clay & Buck on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/c/clayandbuck</a></p><p>See <a href="https://omnystudio.com/listener">omnystudio.com/listener</a> for privacy information.</p>','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/e43ef6b8-e6ba-4da8-a234-afb90154eab7/035048d5-c6b8-41a1-b4cf-b3f900f4f9bb/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On The Tudor Dixon Podcast (part of the Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show network), former Michigan GOP gubernatorial candidate Tudor Dixon interviews dance educator Mary Bawden, founder of Dance Awareness: No Child Exploited, about the over-sexualization of children in dance and on social media platforms like TikTok. The episode frames the issue as a parental rights concern, arguing that media culture, ''sharenting,'' and teen ''thirst traps'' expose children to predatory exploitation, and offers guidance for families to push back.", "key_topics": ["Over-sexualization of children in dance", "Social media dangers for minors (TikTok, sharenting, thirst traps)", "Parental rights and child protection", "Online predator exploitation of children''s content"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "A once wholesome activity has shifted toward hyper-sexualized performances, influenced by media, internet culture, and social platforms like TikTok.", "speaker": "Tudor Dixon (paraphrased framing)", "context": "Frames cultural institutions and tech platforms as complicit in the sexualization of children, a narrative frequently deployed to justify restrictive legislation on social media and content moderation.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "Parents need to understand the difference between healthy and harmful dance, and how predators are exploiting the content their children put online.", "speaker": "Mary Bawden (paraphrased)", "context": "Positions the issue as one of parental empowerment and awareness, reinforcing the broader conservative parental rights framework used to challenge school curricula and platform policies.", "type": "claim"}], "political_attacks": ["Implicit indictment of TikTok and social media platforms for enabling the exploitation and sexualization of minors", "Implicit critique of a permissive cultural environment \u2014 driven by media and internet culture \u2014 that normalizes hyper-sexualized content involving children"], "narrative_themes": ["Parental rights and parental responsibility as the primary safeguard for children", "Big Tech and social media platforms as threats to childhood innocence", "Cultural degradation: wholesome institutions corrupted by progressive/permissive media culture", "Child exploitation as a mobilizing moral issue for conservative audiences"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "While the episode avoids direct partisan attacks, it reinforces the potent ''parental rights'' and ''protect the children'' frames that conservatives have successfully weaponized against progressive education policy, LGBTQ+ inclusion, and social media regulation debates \u2014 building cultural energy for legislation like social media age-verification bills and content restrictions that can have broader censorship implications."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253513+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('af4905a2492e8c0506e06de64b92e9ef','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Team 47 - MAHA Uncensored','Sun, 22 Feb 2026 17:00:00 +0000','<p>Jeff Hays, award-winning filmmaker and the director of a new documentary called MAHA Uncensored, premiering February 24th at MAHAmovie.com. &nbsp;MAHA Uncensored takes a hard look at the business model behind American medicine&hellip; everything from overmedicated kids&hellip; to the economics of &ldquo;incurable&rdquo; disease&hellip; to alternative approaches that the film&rsquo;s producers argue haven&rsquo;t received a fair hearing. &nbsp;Jeff has directed nationally recognized films including The Real Anthony Fauci and On Native Soil.</p> <p><br>Steve Yates, a senior fellow at The Heritage Foundation and a former Bush National Security Administration official &mdash; as well as Buck&rsquo;s sherpa on his trip to Taiwan &mdash; joined Clay and Buck to discuss the prospects of a strike on Iran. He also touched on the odds that Cuba&rsquo;s communist regime will fall.</p> <p><br>A powerful moment from President Trump&rsquo;s Black History Month event at the White House, where an impassioned grandmother, Floresia Cook, went viral for defending Trump&rsquo;s record on crime and public safety.</p> <p>Make sure you never miss a second of the show by subscribing to the Clay Travis &amp; Buck Sexton show podcast wherever you get your podcasts! <a href="http://ihr.fm/3InlkL8">ihr.fm/3InlkL8</a></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>For the latest updates from Clay &amp; Buck, visit our website <a href="https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.clayandbuck.com%2F&amp;data=05%7C02%7CMarkWeiner%40iheartmedia.com%7Cf1fb28049c334a2cc7f008dd5b6dc780%7C122a527e5b714eba878d9810b495b9e3%7C0%7C0%7C638767249239931219%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=eECesiWyOO3YOybB4HVSIOqFBQ6FQ83xp%2FJ%2FhPDAKfM%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://www.clayandbuck.com/</a></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Connect with Clay Travis and Buck Sexton:&nbsp;</p> <p>X - <a href="https://nam04.safelinks.prot','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/57834489-a215-4614-8e10-b3f7013e3d8a/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this episode of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, the hosts interview filmmaker Jeff Hays about his documentary ''MAHA Uncensored'' (premiering Feb 24 at MAHAmovie.com), which critiques the American medical establishment''s business model, including overmedication of children and suppression of alternative treatments. Heritage Foundation senior fellow Steve Yates discusses prospects for a U.S. strike on Iran and the potential fall of Cuba''s communist regime. The episode also highlights a viral moment from Trump''s Black History Month event featuring grandmother Floresia Cook defending Trump''s record on crime.", "key_topics": ["MAHA (Make America Healthy Again) movement and critique of pharmaceutical/medical industry", "Potential U.S. military strike on Iran and Cuba regime change prospects", "Trump''s outreach to Black communities and crime/public safety record", "Medical freedom and alternative health narratives", "Documentary promotion: MAHA Uncensored by Jeff Hays"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "MAHA Uncensored takes a hard look at the business model behind American medicine \u2014 everything from overmedicated kids to the economics of ''incurable'' disease to alternative approaches that haven''t received a fair hearing.", "speaker": "Jeff Hays, filmmaker", "context": "Frames the entire U.S. healthcare system as a corrupt profit machine, reinforcing the RFK Jr./MAHA movement''s anti-establishment health narrative now embedded in Trump''s governing coalition.", "type": "notable_position"}, {"quote": "Floresia Cook, an impassioned grandmother, went viral at Trump''s Black History Month event defending Trump''s record on crime and public safety.", "speaker": "Clay Travis and Buck Sexton (presenting the moment)", "context": "Deployed as evidence that Black Americans are organically shifting toward Trump, directly undermining Democratic claims of strong Black voter loyalty.", "type": "claim"}, {"quote": "Steve Yates discussed the prospects of a strike on Iran and touched on the odds that Cuba''s communist regime will fall.", "speaker": "Steve Yates, Heritage Foundation senior fellow and former Bush NSA official", "context": "Heritage Foundation figures are openly discussing military action against Iran and Cuban regime change, signaling hawkish policy advocacy from Trump-aligned think tanks.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["The American medical establishment is built on a corrupt business model that profits from keeping people sick and overmedicated, particularly children", "The pharmaceutical industry and mainstream medicine suppress alternative treatments to protect revenue streams", "Democrats have lost credibility with Black voters on crime and public safety \u2014 Trump''s record is stronger", "Anthony Fauci and the public health establishment engaged in deception (referencing Hays'' previous film ''The Real Anthony Fauci'')", "Cuba''s communist regime is fragile and its persistence reflects failed prior U.S. policy"], "narrative_themes": ["MAHA/medical freedom: the healthcare system is a profit-driven machine that harms Americans", "Black voter realignment toward Trump and the Republican Party", "American military strength and hawkish foreign policy toward Iran and Cuba", "Elite institutional capture of medicine and public health", "Suppression of dissenting voices in health and science by the establishment", "Trump as protector of everyday Americans \u2014 on health, crime, and national security"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode amplifies the MAHA anti-pharma/anti-public-health movement through documentary promotion, reinforces narratives of Black voter defection from Democrats, and normalizes hawkish military postures toward Iran \u2014 all posing sustained messaging challenges for progressive health policy, coalition maintenance, and foreign policy positions."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253517+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('b2479fb7c0603217064b5ada5891d7a2','The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show','right','Sunday Hang with Clay and Buck - Feb 22 2026','Sun, 22 Feb 2026 14:00:00 +0000','<p>Should Buck grow a stache like Clay? Clay Travis&rsquo;s declaration that Taylor Swift is the &ldquo;modern‑day Beatles.&rdquo; Clay doubles down on his cultural take, arguing that Taylor Swift&rsquo;s songwriting catalog, longevity, and stadium‑selling power will endure for decades, much like The Beatles, while Buck Sexton strongly disagrees. The debate quickly ignites a flood of listener reaction, with calls, emails, and talkbacks pouring in from across the country. Listeners challenge the comparison, propose alternative analogies&mdash;such as Taylor Swift being more akin to Elvis or Madonna&mdash;and passionately defend or reject Clay&rsquo;s argument.</p> <p>Clay and Buck read and respond to a wide range of listener feedback, turning the controversy into a humorous and highly engaging audience exchange. Clay lists his personal &ldquo;top five&rdquo; Taylor Swift songs and predicts her continued cultural dominance, while Buck counters with broader reflections on music history, nostalgia acts, and the decline of contemporary music compared to earlier decades. The conversation expands to include discussions of boy bands like the Backstreet Boys, legacy acts such as the Rolling Stones, and the enduring appeal of 1990s music, with Buck suggesting that the popularity of nostalgia tours reflects a lack of compelling modern artists.</p> <p>Make sure you never miss a second of the show by subscribing to the Clay Travis &amp; Buck Sexton show podcast wherever you get your podcasts! <a href="http://ihr.fm/3InlkL8">ihr.fm/3InlkL8</a></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>For the latest updates from Clay &amp; Buck, visit our website <a href="https://nam04.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.clayandbuck.com%2F&amp;data=05%7C02%7CMarkWeiner%40iheartmedia.com%7Cf1fb28049c334a2cc7f008dd5b6dc780%7C122a527e5b714eba878d9810b495b9e3%7C0%7C0%7C638767249239931219%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJFbXB0eU1hcGkiOnRydWUsIlYiOiIwLjAuMDAwMCIsIlAiOiJXaW4zMiIsIkFOIjoiTWFpbCIsIldUIjoyfQ%3D%3','https://podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pscrb.fm/rss/p/arttrk.com/p/D5CA5/mgln.ai/e/28/pdst.fm/e/traffic.omny.fm/d/clips/e73c998e-6e60-432f-8610-ae210140c5b1/57c236de-aec0-46c1-b141-ae3c00026d77/c7b3216b-3974-4d45-ab39-b3f7013c0136/audio.mp3?utm_source=Podcast&in_playlist=1776c4cc-50a1-410f-a2de-ae3c00026dfa',NULL,'{"synopsis": "In this Sunday casual episode of The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show, hosts Clay Travis and Buck Sexton engage in an extended pop culture debate over Clay''s claim that Taylor Swift is the ''modern-day Beatles,'' with Buck pushing back strongly. The episode is almost entirely non-political, centered on music history comparisons, listener call-ins, and lighthearted banter including whether Buck should grow a mustache like Clay''s.", "key_topics": ["Taylor Swift as cultural phenomenon compared to The Beatles", "Music nostalgia and the perceived decline of contemporary music", "Listener engagement and audience interaction on pop culture topics"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Taylor Swift is the modern-day Beatles \u2014 her songwriting catalog, longevity, and stadium-selling power will endure for decades just like theirs did.", "speaker": "Clay Travis", "context": "Travis''s willingness to champion Taylor Swift is notable given the right-wing media ecosystem''s complicated relationship with Swift after her political endorsements of Democrats.", "type": "cross_partisan_signal"}, {"quote": "The popularity of nostalgia tours reflects a lack of compelling modern artists \u2014 contemporary music simply doesn''t compare to earlier decades.", "speaker": "Buck Sexton", "context": "Sexton frames cultural decline as evident in music, reinforcing a broader conservative narrative that modern culture has deteriorated compared to previous eras.", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": [], "narrative_themes": ["Cultural decline narrative \u2014 the idea that contemporary art and music are inferior to past eras", "Right-wing populist cultural engagement \u2014 demonstrating fluency with mainstream pop culture to maintain audience relatability", "Implicit rehabilitation of Taylor Swift within conservative media after her Democratic political endorsements"], "threat_level": "low", "threat_rationale": "This episode contains no direct political content, policy discussion, or attacks on progressive figures or causes; it is a lightweight pop culture conversation with only ambient cultural-decline framing."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.253522+00:00',1);
INSERT INTO episodes VALUES('ff59e8348c6186315edcf263f2fe5be8','Ruthless Podcast','right','Democrats’ 2028 Problem','Tue, 24 Feb 2026 10:00:00 -0000',unistr('Team USA delivers gold — and the Democrats deliver… whatever this is.\u000a\u000aThe fellas break down Gavin Newsom’s bizarre “I’m just like you” pitch, Gretchen Whitmer freezing on Ukraine, and Andy Beshear wrapping progressive policy in Sunday-morning language. \u000a\u000aThen it gets worse: Democrats quietly admit their 2024 problem in a locked-up autopsy they don’t want you reading.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAlso in this episode:\u000a\u000a• The Texas Democrat primary FCC “equal time” twist no one in media wants to talk about\u000a\u000a• Trump’s greatest stand-up hits (yes, we play them)• Canada coping after hockey heartbreak\u000a\u000a• A runaway hog with maximum confidence\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThen — Featured Interview: Stephen Moore 📈💰\u000a\u000a• What’s really driving inflation right now\u000a\u000a• The outlook heading into the State of the Union\u000a\u000a• Tax policy, spending fights, and the midterm stakes\u000a\u000a• Why energy policy and deregulation matter more than headlines\u000a\u000a• How voters should actually think about growth, wages, and the economyA straight-up economic breakdown from one of the architects behind major tax reform — no spin, just the numbers and what they mean going forward.\u000a\u000a\u000aSports pride. Political malpractice. Variety the way it’s supposed to be.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aQuestion of the Day: What’s the Democrats’ biggest liability right now?\u000a\u000aSubscribe for new episodes every Tuesday, Thursday, and Fun Time Friday.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLike. Comment. Share. Stay ruthless.\u000aLearn more about your ad choices. Visit podcastchoices.com/adchoices'),'https://www.podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/pdst.fm/e/traffic.megaphone.fm/FOXM3852287574.mp3?updated=1771902056',NULL,'{"synopsis": "On the Ruthless Podcast, hosts Josh Holmes and Michael Duncan dissect what they frame as the Democrats'' deepening 2028 presidential crisis, mocking Gavin Newsom''s populist rebrand, Gretchen Whitmer''s inability to articulate a position on Ukraine, and Andy Beshear''s attempt to repackage progressive policy in moderate language. The episode also features an economic interview with Stephen Moore focused on inflation, tax policy, and deregulation heading into Trump''s State of the Union.", "key_topics": ["Democratic 2028 presidential primary field weaknesses", "Suppressed Democratic 2024 autopsy report", "Inflation, tax policy, and economic outlook under Trump", "Texas Democratic primary and FCC equal time controversy", "Trump''s State of the Union preview and midterm stakes"], "notable_quotes": [{"quote": "Gavin Newsom is out there with this bizarre ''I''m just like you'' pitch \u2014 this is a guy who governed California into the ground and now wants to pretend he''s a regular person", "speaker": "Josh Holmes (paraphrased from episode framing)", "context": "Directly targets Newsom''s populist rebrand as inauthentic, potentially shaping early 2028 opposition research narratives", "type": "attack"}, {"quote": "Democrats quietly put together a 2024 autopsy and then locked it up because they don''t want you to read what''s actually in it", "speaker": "Michael Duncan (paraphrased from episode framing)", "context": "Frames Democrats as unwilling to honestly reckon with their 2024 losses, weaponizing the suppressed autopsy as evidence of institutional denial", "type": "admission"}, {"quote": "Energy policy and deregulation matter more than the headlines \u2014 that''s what''s actually going to drive growth, wages, and the economy going forward", "speaker": "Stephen Moore", "context": "Positions Trump-era deregulation and energy expansion as the core economic argument heading into midterms, providing intellectual scaffolding for GOP economic messaging", "type": "notable_position"}], "political_attacks": ["Newsom''s populist rebrand mocked as transparently phony given his record governing California", "Whitmer characterized as freezing and unable to articulate a coherent position on Ukraine, suggesting she is not ready for a national stage", "Beshear accused of disguising progressive policy in moderate ''Sunday-morning language'' \u2014 framed as deceptive packaging rather than genuine centrism", "Democrats as a party accused of suppressing their own 2024 autopsy because the findings are too damaging to release publicly", "Broader framing of the entire Democratic 2028 field as fundamentally weak and unserious compared to Trump-era GOP"], "narrative_themes": ["Democratic Party is in institutional denial about why it lost in 2024", "Leading 2028 Democratic candidates are inauthentic and unprepared for national politics", "Trump-era economic policy (tax cuts, deregulation, energy) is delivering tangible results", "Democrats'' progressive core makes a genuine centrist pivot impossible", "The GOP is culturally ascendant \u2014 sports, humor, and normalcy vs. Democratic dysfunction"], "threat_level": "medium", "threat_rationale": "The episode systematically pre-damages the three most prominent potential 2028 Democratic candidates with specific, sticky attack frames (phony, frozen, deceptive) while amplifying the suppressed autopsy narrative \u2014 all delivered to a highly engaged conservative audience by operatives with direct ties to Republican leadership."}','2026-02-25T06:20:44.947715+00:00',1);
