ue, 24 Feb 2026 08:00:00 -0500\u000a  "Democracy Now! 2026-02-24 Tuesday"\u000a  This episode of Democracy Now! covers four major stories: the intensification of nor''easters due to climate change featuring climate scientist Michael Mann, the U.S.-aided killing of a top Mexican cartel leader amid Trump''s threats of military intervention in Mexico, the release of Epstein files, Duterte''s ICC case, and the anniversary of Russia''s war in Ukraine with war crimes prosecutor Reed Brody. The episode frames these stories through a progressive lens emphasizing climate accountability, concerns about U.S. militarism abroad, and international justice.\u000a  Topics: Climate change intensifying extreme weather events (nor''easters), U.S. intelligence cooperation with Mexican military to kill cartel leader under Trump intervention threats, Epstein files release and accountability, Duterte ICC prosecution for extrajudicial killings\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Democracy Now!  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 08:00:00 -0500\u000a  "Democracy Now! 2026-02-23 Monday"\u000a  This episode of Democracy Now! covers three major stories: the Supreme Court''s decision to limit Trump''s power to impose tariffs and his subsequent attacks on the justices; Palestinian poet Mosab Abu Toha''s firsthand account challenging the characterization of the Gaza ''ceasefire,'' arguing conditions still constitute genocide; and the controversy surrounding U.S. Olympians who have publicly opposed the Trump administration, drawing attacks from Trump while FBI Director Kash Patel is seen partying. The episode frames these as interconnected examples of authoritarian overreach and democratic erosion.\u000a  Topics: Supreme Court limiting Trump''s tariff authority and Trump''s attacks on justices, Gaza ceasefire conditions and ongoing humanitarian crisis characterized as genocide, U.S. Olympians clashing with the Trump administration and Kash Patel''s conduct\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Fresh Air (NPR)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 20:11:07 +0000\u000a  "Tayari Jones on friendship, writing, and choosing your ‘Kin’"\u000a  This episode of Fresh Air features interviewer Tonya Mosley speaking with novelist Tayari Jones about her new novel ''Kin,'' set in the Jim Crow South, which explores female friendship, loss, and class divides through two girls growing up without their mothers. Jones discusses her civil rights activist parents, the grief of losing a friendship, and her creative process. The episode is primarily a cultural/literary interview with no direct political policy debate.\u000a  Topics: Jim Crow South as literary and historical setting, Female friendship and chosen family across class lines, Civil rights movement legacy and intergenerational activism, Black women''s literature and cultural representation\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Fresh Air (NPR)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:11:55 +0000\u000a  "Kate Hudson"\u000a  This episode of Fresh Air, hosted by co-host Tonya Mosley, is a celebrity interview with actress and entrepreneur Kate Hudson about her debut music album ''Glorious,'' her Oscar-nominated role in ''Song Sung Blue,'' and reflections on her career including ''Almost Famous.'' The conversation is entirely focused on arts, entertainment, and personal life — there is no political content.\u000a  Topics: Kate Hudson''s music career, celebrity personal reflection and motherhood, film career retrospective\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Majority Report  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:03:00 +0000\u000a  "3586 - Corruption and Trump''s Major SCOTUS Tariff Loss w/ Mark Joseph Stern"\u000a  This episode of the Majority Report covers FBI Director Kash Patel''s hypocrisy on taxpayer-funded personal travel, Trump''s incoherent attack on NYC mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani, and features Slate''s Mark Joseph Stern analyzing the Supreme Court''s major ruling striking down Trump''s tariffs. The show also highlights Trump''s catastrophic -47 point polling with independents, growing disconnect between Democratic voters and party leadership, and buyer''s remorse from right-leaning media figures Saager Enjeti and Andrew Schulz over their Trump support.\u000a  Topics: Supreme Court tariff ruling against Trump, Kash Patel taxpayer-funded travel hypocrisy, Trump polling collapse with independents (-47 points), Democratic party leadership disconnect with base\u000a\u000a[LEFT] The Daily (NYT)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 10:45:00 +0000\u000a  "Trump Weighs War With Iran"\u000a  This episode of The Daily (NYT) features White House and National Security Correspondent David E. Sanger analyzing President Trump''s consideration of military strikes against Iran amid a concurrent U.S. military buildup and planned diplomatic talks. The episode examines Trump''s strategic rationale—or lack thereof—for potential military action, noting that he has publicly declined to articulate a clear justification for why he is pursuing this course or why now. The discussion frames a tension between the administration''s dual-track approach of military escalation and last-minute diplomacy.\u000a  Topics: Trump administration consideration of targeted military strikes against Iran, U.S. military buildup around Iran and escalating tensions, Absence of a clear public justification or casus belli from the White House, Diplomatic negotiations planned between U.S. and Iran later in the week\u000a\u000a[LEFT] The Daily (NYT)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 10:45:00 +0000\u000a  "Chaos, Confusion and Defiance: The Global Fallout From the Tariff Ruling"\u000a  This episode of The Daily (NYT) examines the Supreme Court''s ruling that President Trump exceeded his authority in imposing sweeping tariffs on nearly every U.S. trading partner, and Trump''s defiant response of announcing a new 15 percent global tariff. Reporters Tyler Pager, Ana Swanson, and Andrew Ross Sorkin discuss the constitutional clash, market chaos, and global diplomatic fallout from Trump''s insistence on expansive executive power over trade policy.\u000a  Topics: Supreme Court ruling striking down Trump''s sweeping tariffs as exceeding presidential authority, Trump''s defiant response: announcing a new 15% global tariff despite the ruling, Constitutional separation of powers and the limits of executive authority on trade, Global economic and diplomatic fallout from tariff uncertainty\u000a\u000a[LEFT] The Ezra Klein Show  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 10:00:00 +0000\u000a  "How Quickly Will A.I. Agents Rip Through the Economy?"\u000a  On The Ezra Klein Show, host Ezra Klein interviews Jack Clark, co-founder of Anthropic, about the transition from AI chatbots to AI agents (like Claude Code) and what this shift means for the economy, labor markets, and policy. The conversation probes whether agentic AI will deliver meaningful productivity gains, how fast job displacement could occur, and what government responses—including monitoring and potential safety nets—are needed. The episode frames this as a pivotal economic and political moment, with Clark arguing capabilities are still rapidly improving while acknowledging deep uncertainty about real-world impact.\u000a  Topics: AI agents and the shift from chatbot to agentic AI era, Economic productivity and labor market displacement from AI, Government AI monitoring, regulation, and policy responses, Anthropic''s role and positioning in the AI industry\u000a\u000a[LEFT] The Indicator (NPR/Planet Money)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 08:00:00 +0000\u000a  "Do traders who place big bets make big money?"\u000a  This episode of NPR''s The Indicator from Planet Money examines ''option whales'' — large-scale financial traders who place outsized bets on options contracts — and investigates whether these big bets consistently pay off. The episode explores the mechanics of options trading, the risks involved, and the broader market dynamics created by these large traders. It also references a related earlier episode on congressional stock trading via the platform Unusual Whales.\u000a  Topics: Options trading and market speculation, Financial market whales and outsized bets, Risk and reward dynamics in derivatives markets\u000a\u000a[LEFT] The Indicator (NPR/Planet Money)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 08:00:02 +0000\u000a  "Why there are roving rotisserie chicken mobs"\u000a  This listener Q&A episode of NPR''s The Indicator from Planet Money tackles three topics: whether AI job interviewers exhibit bias, what M2 money supply is and why it matters, and the viral phenomenon of frenzied consumers fighting over rotisserie chickens at grocery stores — likely driven by rising beef and poultry prices pushing demand toward budget-friendly prepared chicken options. The episode connects consumer behavior to broader food inflation dynamics.\u000a  Topics: AI bias in hiring and job interviews, M2 money supply and monetary policy, Food price inflation and consumer behavior around rotisserie chicken demand\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Throughline (NPR)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 08:05:00 +0000\u000a  "How the Civil War changed how we vote"\u000a  This episode of NPR''s Throughline examines how the 1864 presidential election, occurring amid the Civil War and in the wake of the Emancipation Proclamation, fundamentally transformed American democracy — reshaping voting rights, the meaning of democratic participation, and national identity. The episode argues that Lincoln''s political gamble in issuing the Emancipation Proclamation forced the country to confront whether its democracy would be truly inclusive, with lasting consequences for how and who votes in America.\u000a  Topics: 1864 presidential election and its impact on voting rights, Lincoln''s Emancipation Proclamation as a political and moral turning point, Civil War-era expansion of democratic participation and its modern legacy\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Up First (NPR)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 11:08:05 +0000\u000a  "Trump State of the Union Strategy, Mexico Cartel Violence, Epstein Files Naming Trump"\u000a  This episode of NPR''s Up First covers three major stories: President Trump''s strategic challenge heading into his State of the Union address amid new NPR polling showing 60% of Americans believe the country is worse off than a year ago; escalating cartel violence in Mexico following the military killing of drug lord El Mencho; and an NPR investigation revealing the Justice Department removed or withheld dozens of pages from the Epstein files database that include allegations mentioning President Trump, contradicting the administration''s claims of full transparency.\u000a  Topics: Trump State of the Union strategy amid cratering public confidence, Mexico cartel violence and destabilization following El Mencho killing, DOJ suppression of Epstein files pages mentioning Trump\u000a\u000a[LEFT] Up First (NPR)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 10:59:40 +0000\u000a  "Trump''s New Tariffs, China Reacts To Tariff Ruling, State Of The Union Poll"\u000a  This episode of NPR''s Up First covers three major stories: President Trump''s pivot to raising global tariffs to 15% under alternative legal authority after the Supreme Court blocked his emergency tariff powers, China''s strategic calculus in response to the ruling ahead of Trump''s planned Beijing trip, and a new NPR/PBS News/Marist poll showing most Americans believe the state of the union is not strong heading into Trump''s Tuesday address. The episode frames the tariff maneuver as forcing congressional Republicans into a difficult position during a midterm election year.\u000a  Topics: Trump''s 15% global tariff under alternative statutory authority after Supreme Court ruling, China''s strategic response to the court ruling and implications for Trump''s upcoming Beijing trip, NPR/PBS News/Marist poll showing Americans view state of the union as weak ahead of presidential address\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] Americast (BBC)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 01:30:00 +0000\u000a  "Russia''s Church in Texas"\u000a  This episode of BBC''s Americast (via their Documentary/Assignment strand) examines how growing numbers of American Catholics and Protestants in Texas are converting to Eastern Orthodoxy, drawn by traditional liturgy and a rejection of what they see as ''woke'' drift in mainstream churches. Reporter Lucy Ash investigates how this religious migration intersects with a dramatic realignment in US-Russia relations under Trump''s second term, including the White House voting against a UN resolution condemning Russia''s invasion of Ukraine, and how some converts with large online followings actively amplify Kremlin narratives that Russia is the last bastion of true Christianity.\u000a  Topics: American conversions to Eastern Orthodoxy as cultural-political phenomenon, US-Russia relations realignment under Trump''s second term, Religious right''s rejection of progressive social causes framed as churches going ''woke'', Kremlin narrative amplification through American religious influencers\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] Americast (BBC)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 12:00:00 +0000\u000a  "The Dream Makers"\u000a  This episode of Americast (BBC), reported by Anand Jagatia, explores the emerging field of dream engineering — the science of influencing human thoughts during sleep. The episode examines both the potential benefits (memory enhancement, creativity, wellbeing) and the serious ethical concerns around an unregulated technology that could commercialize access to the human subconscious. This is a science/technology feature rather than a political episode.\u000a  Topics: Dream engineering and neurotechnology, Ethical concerns over manipulation of the subconscious, Lack of regulation for emerging cognitive technologies\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] Americast (BBC)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 01:30:00 +0000\u000a  "Jason Gilkison: Choreographer for Strictly Come Dancing"\u000a  This episode of Americast (BBC), hosted by Katie Derham, is entirely non-political in nature. It features an interview with Jason Gilkison, the longtime choreographer for Strictly Come Dancing (the UK version of Dancing with the Stars), along with TV director Nikki Parsons and costume designer Vicky Gill, discussing the creative and technical process behind producing dance spectaculars for television, including behind-the-scenes preparation for the Strictly Come Dancing 2025 final.\u000a  Topics: Television choreography and production for Strictly Come Dancing, Creative collaboration between choreographer, TV director, and costume designer, Behind-the-scenes look at producing a live dance show finale\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] Hidden Brain (NPR)  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 20:00:00 +0000\u000a  "Do You Feel Invisible?"\u000a  This episode of Hidden Brain (NPR), hosted by Shankar Vedantam, explores the psychology of ''mattering'' — the feeling of being valued and significant — through an interview with psychologist Gordon Flett of York University. The episode argues that feeling invisible or overlooked fuels loneliness, depression, and even violence, and that simple gestures can rebuild a sense of meaning. The second half features psychologist Marc Berman answering listener questions about the healing effects of nature.\u000a  Topics: Psychology of mattering and feeling invisible, Loneliness, depression, and suicide as public health crises, Connection between lack of mattering and violence, Therapeutic and psychological benefits of nature exposure\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] Pivot (Vox Media)  |  Tue, 24 Feb 2026 11:00:00 -0000\u000a  "Tariff Turmoil, Trump''s Netflix Threat, and SOTU Predictions"\u000a  On this episode of Pivot, Kara Swisher and Scott Galloway analyze the Supreme Court''s ruling against Trump''s tariff authority, his retaliatory threat against Netflix over board member Susan Rice, and Democratic strategy heading into the State of the Union. The hosts also discuss the emerging ''HALO'' stocks investment thesis and Galloway''s ongoing ''Resist and Unsubscribe'' campaign targeting corporate compliance with the Trump administration.\u000a  Topics: Supreme Court ruling striking down Trump''s tariff authority and potential refund obligations, Trump threatening Netflix over board member Susan Rice — corporate intimidation and First Amendment concerns, Democratic strategy for the State of the Union address, HALO stocks as an emerging investor framework\u000a\u000a[NEUTRAL] The NPR Politics Podcast  |  Mon, 23 Feb 2026 21:38:29 +0000\u000a  "What to watch in the race for North Carolina''s open Senate seat"\u000a  This episode of The NPR Politics Podcast, hosted by voting correspondent Miles Parks with political correspondent Ashley Lopez and WUNC Capitol Bureau Chief Colin Campbell, covers North Carolina''s upcoming primary election with a focus on the open U.S. Senate race and a competitive Democratic primary in the state''s 4th congressional district. The discussion examines the candidate fields, early voting dynamics, and what the outcomes could signal for both parties heading into the 2026 midterms.\u000a  Topics: North Carolina open Senate seat primary race, Competitive Democratic primary in NC-4 congressional district, Early voting trends and primary dynamics in North Carolina\u000a'),'2026-02-24T22:46:50.760057+00:00');
INSERT INTO digests VALUES('20260225','February 25, 2026',unistr('<!DOCTYPE html>\u000a<html lang="en">\u000a<head>\u000a<meta charset="utf-8">\u000a<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1">\u000a<title>CAP Podcast Intelligence — February 25, 2026</title>\u000a</head>\u000a<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background:#f0f2f5;font-family:Georgia,serif;color:#1a1a2e;">\u000a<div style="max-width:700px;margin:0 auto;padding:24px 16px;">\u000a\u000a  <div style="background:#1a3a5c;border-radius:8px 8px 0 0;padding:24px 32px;">\u000a    <div style="font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7fb3d3;font-family:sans-serif;margin-bottom:4px;">Center for American Progress</div>\u000a    <div style="font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#ffffff;letter-spacing:-.3px;">Podcast Intelligence Report</div>\u000a    <div style="font-size:13px;color:#a8cce0;margin-top:6px;font-family:sans-serif;">February 25, 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; 64 episodes analyzed</div>\u000a  </div>\u000a  <div style="background:#c0392b;padding:8px 32px;font-family:sans-serif;font-size:11px;color:white;letter-spacing:.5px;">\u000a    &#9888; CONFIDENTIAL — FOR CAP INTERNAL AND CAMPAIGN USE ONLY\u000a  </div>\u000a\u000a  <div style="background:#ffffff;padding:32px;border-radius:0 0 8px 8px;box-shadow:0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.07);">\u000a\u000a    <div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#888;margin-bottom:16px;">TODAY AT A GLANCE</div>\u000a    <div style="display:flex;gap:14px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:36px;"><div style="flex:1;min-width:200px;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-top:3px solid #c0392b;border-radius:6px;padding:18px 20px;"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1.5px;color:#c0392b;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:12px;font-family:sans-serif;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</div><ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:13.5px;"><li style="margin:7px 0;line-height:1.6;color:#2c3e50;">Sam Seder sharply criticized Democrats'' choice of Colonial Williamsburg as the backdrop for Gov. Spanberger''s State of the Union response, calling it a tone-deaf evocation of slaveholding history that undercuts the party''s forward-looking message.</li></ul></div><div style="flex:1;min-width:200px;background:#f4f6f7;border:1px solid #c0c9d0;border-top:3px solid #5d6d7e;border-radius:6px;padding:18px 20px;"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1.5px;color:#5d6d7e;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:12px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚪ CENTER / NEUTRAL</div><ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:13.5px;"><li style="margin:7px 0;line-height:1.6;color:#2c3e50;">NPR''s post-State of the Union analysis identified Trump''s core midterm strategy as economic populism paired with immigration enforcement, with Mara Liasson and Domenico Montanaro noting Democrats lack a coherent counter-narrative.</li><li style="margin:7px 0;line-height:1.6;color:#2c3e50;">NPR flagged that Trump used the State of the Union to frame Democrats as obstructionists standing against working Americans'' economic interests — a populist wedge that comms teams should prepare to counter directly.</li><li style="margin:7px 0;line-height:1.6;color:#2c3e50;">The BBC''s Americast offered no political content today, running only a cross-promoted human interest segment, leaving NPR as the sole substantive centrist voice covering the State of the Union.</li></ul></div><div style="flex:1;min-width:200px;background:#eaf4fb;border:1px solid #aed6f1;border-top:3px solid #1a5276;border-radius:6px;padding:18px 20px;"><div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1.5px;color:#1a5276;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:12px;font-family:sans-serif;">🔵 LEFT / PROGRESSIVE</div><ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:13.5px;"><li style="margin:7px 0;line-height:1.6;color:#2c3e50;">Crowder is using Canada''s universal healthcare system as a direct cautionary tale against Medicare for All, framing long wait times and limited access as inherent failures of single-payer — expect this frame to intensify heading into midterms.</li></ul></div></div>\u000a\u000a    <div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;color:#888;border-top:1px solid #e8ecef;padding-top:28px;margin-bottom:16px;">NOTABLE MOMENTS &amp; QUOTES</div>\u000a    <div style="margin-bottom:36px;"><div style="border-left:3px solid #1a5276;background:#eaf4fb;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#1a5276;background:#eaf4fb;border:1px solid #aed6f1;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔵 LEFT / PROGRESSIVE</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">Majority Report</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;Cartel hitmen wear masks. Leftists aren''t complaining.&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Sen. Mike Lee (R-UT)</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Lee''s tweet was used by Democratic senators to highlight the hypocrisy of ICE agents also wearing masks during enforcement operations, turning a GOP attack line into a boomerang moment.</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">Louder with Crowder</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;The thin veneer of Canadian niceness has melted under the heat of the Winter Olympics... Well, at least they still have exceeding long waits to receive limited healthcare.&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Steven Crowder</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Crowder uses the Olympics as a vehicle to attack Canada''s single-payer healthcare system, a persistent right-wing frame against progressive healthcare proposals in the U.S.</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">Morning Wire</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;Mamdani struggles to shovel New York out from under a blizzard&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Evening Wire hosts (framing)</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Frames progressive NYC Mayor Zohran Mamdani as unable to handle basic municipal governance, reinforcing the right''s narrative that progressive leaders are incompetent administrators.</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">Ruthless Podcast</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;Gavin Newsom is out there with this bizarre ''I''m just like you'' pitch — this is a guy who governed California into the ground and now wants to pretend he''s a regular person&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Josh Holmes (paraphrased from episode framing)</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Directly targets Newsom''s populist rebrand as inauthentic, potentially shaping early 2028 opposition research narratives</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">The Ben Shapiro Show</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;Candace Owens is an evil, twisted human being... She is a grifter who is making money off of you by telling you lies that are unbelievably stupid but evocative.&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Ben Shapiro</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Major intra-right schism: Shapiro publicly escalating his war against Owens, one of the most-followed right-wing media figures, over her conspiracy theories targeting the Kirk family.</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;padding:14px 18px;margin-bottom:14px;"><div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;"><span style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.8px;color:#c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border:1px solid #e8b0b0;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;">🔴 RIGHT-WING</span><span style="font-size:11px;font-weight:700;color:#c0392b;background:#c0392b18;border-radius:3px;padding:2px 7px;font-family:sans-serif;">⚔️ ATTACK</span><span style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#666;">The Benny Johnson Show</span></div><blockquote style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;color:#2c3e50;line-height:1.6;">&ldquo;Gavin Newsom just ended his political career by calling Black voters dumb to their faces, live on stage.&rdquo;</blockquote><div style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:#555;"><strong>&mdash; Benny Johnson</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; <em>Johnson frames Newsom''s remarks as catastrophic for his political future, reinforcing a narrative that Democrats are condescending toward Black Americans.</em></div></div><div style="border-left:3px solid #c0392b;background:#fdf2f2;border-