ve weaponized against cosmopolitan or China-adjacent public figures.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "HuffPost scolded Americans for cheering on their own hockey team, and they got absolutely destroyed for it — that tells you everything about where the left is culturally right now."\u000a  — John Minadakis (Jimmy''s Famous Seafood co-owner)\u000a  Guest amplifies the narrative that progressive media is out of touch with mainstream American sentiment, turning a sports moment into a political indictment.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "Democrats'' cultural instincts are increasingly out of step with normal people — when you can''t even celebrate a gold medal without getting lectured, you''ve lost the country."\u000a  — Buck Sexton\u000a  Sexton positions Democratic cultural politics as fundamentally alienating to ordinary Americans, a framing aimed at eroding Democratic support among moderates.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "Democrats can''t be normal — they see a bunch of young American guys singing the national anthem and celebrating a gold medal, and their instinct is to find something wrong with it."\u000a  — Clay Travis\u000a  Encapsulates the episode''s central framing that progressive backlash to patriotic displays is politically toxic and culturally alienating.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "The far left cannot tolerate anything celebratory occurring under Trump''s presidency — that''s what this whole hockey controversy is really about."\u000a  — Bill O''Reilly\u000a  Frames liberal criticism of the White House hockey visit as reflexive anti-Trump partisanship rather than substantive objection, a narrative designed to delegitimize progressive cultural criticism.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "Gavin Newsom is out there doing his ''I can''t read, I''m just like you'' routine with the SAT scores, and the media is helping him build this blue-collar rebrand instead of asking why the governor of the largest state is bragging about being uninformed."\u000a  — Mary Katharine Ham (paraphrased from episode description)\u000a  Frames Newsom''s 2028 positioning as fundamentally dishonest and media-assisted, a key attack line against his anticipated presidential run.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "Bernie Sanders can''t answer a simple follow-up about why the United States produces more successful businesses than Europe. ''Tax the billionaires'' is not a plan — it''s a bumper sticker."\u000a  — Mary Katharine Ham and/or Karol Markowicz (paraphrased from episode description)\u000a  Directly undermines Sanders'' credibility as an economic voice and frames progressive taxation arguments as intellectually empty.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "Politicians prioritize the comfort of foreign criminals over the safety of American citizens... your pain has been censored and suppressed for political purposes."\u000a  — President Trump (as played/quoted by Buck Sexton)\u000a  Trump''s remarks at the Angel Families event directly accuse Democratic politicians of complicity in violence against Americans, a framing designed to emotionally anchor immigration enforcement to victim narratives.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "The press does not give enough attention to the bravery, composure, and risk that President Trump continues to face. This man has been shot in the ear, and now someone scales a fence at Mar-a-Lago with a shotgun and gasoline."\u000a  — Buck Sexton\u000a  Sexton frames media coverage of threats against Trump as deliberately insufficient, reinforcing a narrative of media bias and Trump as a uniquely persecuted figure.\u000a\u000a[RIGHT] The Clay Travis & Buck Sexton Show — ATTACK\u000a  "The mainstream media has long focuse